[SPEAKER_17]: Excellent.

195
00:20:51,058 --> 00:20:55,221
[SPEAKER_17]: And then in the accessory uses, you can see the differentiation here.

196
00:20:55,281 --> 00:21:02,506
[SPEAKER_17]: Some of these are exempt uses and other things that we've seen in the other zonings that we've been doing.

197
00:21:03,507 --> 00:21:07,148
[SPEAKER_17]: So that table of uses, this is a separate section of the zoning.

198
00:21:07,388 --> 00:21:11,189
[SPEAKER_17]: I'm going to move to the Boston Avenue Neighborhood Corridor itself.

199
00:21:11,769 --> 00:21:13,809
[SPEAKER_17]: So you'll see it starts off with a purpose.

200
00:21:13,849 --> 00:21:17,330
[SPEAKER_17]: This is similar to the other districts that we've talked about.

201
00:21:17,630 --> 00:21:22,772
[SPEAKER_17]: And all of the zoning that we've been working on, it's primarily mixed use.

202
00:21:22,852 --> 00:21:31,874
[SPEAKER_17]: So you see the variety of uses and building types, supporting jobs, economic development, housing, living within walking distance of jobs, goods, and services.

203
00:21:31,894 --> 00:21:33,094
[SPEAKER_17]: That's been consistent.

204
00:21:33,574 --> 00:21:46,466
[SPEAKER_17]: Where this one differs a little bit is the idea of thinking about these transitions to and from the Tufts University campus and allowing working and learning along Boston Avenue.

205
00:21:47,887 --> 00:21:56,335
[SPEAKER_17]: And then the rest are fairly similar in terms of mixed use, multifamily, and commercial uses as a density to reinforce that non-vehicular travel.

206
00:21:57,295 --> 00:22:04,719
[SPEAKER_17]: and the development standards, and I'll talk a little bit about more of those to provide the landscape and height buffers that have been part of our conversations.

207
00:22:06,140 --> 00:22:09,322
[SPEAKER_17]: So Paula started off with height, because it's the easiest thing to see.

208
00:22:09,382 --> 00:22:13,304
[SPEAKER_17]: So this just shows the base height of three, four, and six.

209
00:22:13,924 --> 00:22:24,070
[SPEAKER_17]: And then with incentives, the additional stories provided that a developer can prove that they have met one or more of the criteria.

210
00:22:24,570 --> 00:22:26,111
[SPEAKER_17]: in the table of incentives.

211
00:22:26,611 --> 00:22:48,058
[SPEAKER_17]: And they're very similar to the ones that we've talked about most recently for Medford Square in terms of additional affordability, number of units or depth of affordability, preservation of historic buildings or components of the historic buildings, preservation of either local businesses or existing businesses, some parking in the incentives.

212
00:22:48,098 --> 00:22:51,680
[SPEAKER_17]: So that menu is the same as it was for Medford Square.

213
00:22:52,800 --> 00:23:13,263
[SPEAKER_17]: Other key things that we're looking at, the other dimensional standards, the lot area you certainly saw in BA1 that there are quite small lots there so tying the frontages to that we have the facade build out which is how much of the frontage, the frontage is that

214
00:23:14,244 --> 00:23:31,740
[SPEAKER_17]: Lot line along the street, the front lot line, it's the length of that is the frontage and the facade build out is how much of that frontage has a building, has some sort of principle facade which may be that mixed use commercial and residential or all residential or all commercial.

215
00:23:32,600 --> 00:23:40,526
[SPEAKER_17]: We talk about and have defined active ground floor uses, allowing historical conversions again, and then the setbacks.

216
00:23:40,746 --> 00:23:59,600
[SPEAKER_17]: And although they are zero, remembering that consistent with the other zoning districts, including most recently Medford Square, that from a residential district, there is a setback requirement of 10 feet, and then there are step back requirements at the upper levels as well.

217
00:24:00,040 --> 00:24:03,684
[SPEAKER_17]: and those are covered in the text of the dimensional standards.

218
00:24:04,385 --> 00:24:06,127
[SPEAKER_17]: We have building coverage maximums.

219
00:24:06,267 --> 00:24:10,072
[SPEAKER_17]: We also have a green score minimum of 25 and an ideal of 30.

220
00:24:10,452 --> 00:24:13,035
[SPEAKER_17]: That ideal is also one of the incentives.

221
00:24:13,696 --> 00:24:20,043
[SPEAKER_17]: Pervious surface, which is the surfaces that allow for infiltration of water, stormwater primarily.

222
00:25:09,560 --> 00:25:20,814
[SPEAKER_17]: A waiver that if you cannot develop because of these step back requirements that would have to be approved to the community development board to offer a waiver.

223
00:25:20,834 --> 00:25:25,180
[SPEAKER_17]: A waiver for a drop off zone to allow for better management of the curbs.

224
00:25:26,481 --> 00:25:30,545
[SPEAKER_17]: and a waiver for dimensional standards for eligible historic buildings.

225
00:25:30,605 --> 00:25:32,828
[SPEAKER_17]: Again we introduced those in Medford Square.

226
00:25:34,069 --> 00:25:46,302
[SPEAKER_17]: For use standards we have used standards for this conversion of historic buildings to additional residential units and those are consistent again with the ones that we most recently prepared for Medford Square.

227
00:25:46,882 --> 00:25:50,465
[SPEAKER_17]: And then we have new use standards for the drive-through pharmacies.

228
00:25:51,305 --> 00:25:55,188
[SPEAKER_17]: Primarily these, I'm not expecting everybody to read these on the slide.

229
00:25:55,248 --> 00:25:59,911
[SPEAKER_17]: They will be available after the meeting, but they're mostly related to queuing.

230
00:25:59,951 --> 00:26:05,215
[SPEAKER_17]: We understand, of course, that people are concerned about traffic along Boston Avenue.

231
00:26:05,255 --> 00:26:10,359
[SPEAKER_17]: We don't want to drive through to make that work, make that worse by having stacking

232
00:26:12,101 --> 00:26:18,608
[SPEAKER_17]: on the street, so they're required to have sufficient space to queue for a drive-through window on site.

233
00:26:19,069 --> 00:26:25,617
[SPEAKER_17]: There are also requirements about the design of the lanes and the design of the signage.

234
00:26:27,078 --> 00:26:32,284
[SPEAKER_17]: And then finally as Director Hunter mentioned we did have a public meeting on Monday.

235
00:26:32,324 --> 00:26:33,646
[SPEAKER_17]: We had great attendance.

236
00:26:34,807 --> 00:26:36,249
[SPEAKER_17]: Thrilled to see so many there.

237
00:26:36,769 --> 00:26:40,734
[SPEAKER_17]: We had a lot of good questions about the zoning itself.

238
00:26:40,834 --> 00:26:43,437
[SPEAKER_17]: Some of them we were able to answer there.

239
00:26:45,459 --> 00:26:50,664
[SPEAKER_17]: And I apologize if our summary does not meet with somebody's individual comment.

240
00:26:50,744 --> 00:26:53,567
[SPEAKER_17]: We did have general support for four stories.

241
00:26:53,607 --> 00:26:55,308
[SPEAKER_17]: That doesn't mean that everybody agreed.

242
00:26:55,749 --> 00:26:59,272
[SPEAKER_17]: We did hear some concerns about eight story buildings in BA3.

243
00:26:59,673 --> 00:27:04,738
[SPEAKER_17]: We had a lot of concerns about the transition from residential districts to the corridor.

244
00:27:04,818 --> 00:27:06,720
[SPEAKER_17]: That's consistent with what we've heard before.

245
00:27:08,121 --> 00:27:15,747
[SPEAKER_17]: And so we pointed them to some of the things that we've already done in terms of the step backs and the setbacks.

246
00:27:16,327 --> 00:27:32,120
[SPEAKER_17]: And then we had some more suggestions for incentive zoning that were really quite interesting in terms of a minimum percentage of owner occupancy, a requirement to hire local companies as part of the contracting for any new buildings.

247
00:27:32,700 --> 00:27:35,602
[SPEAKER_17]: and remediation of soil in industrial areas.

248
00:27:35,842 --> 00:27:39,304
[SPEAKER_17]: We did talk through with other colleagues in our firm.

249
00:27:40,205 --> 00:27:43,447
[SPEAKER_17]: Generally zoning doesn't speak to owner occupancy.

250
00:27:44,427 --> 00:27:46,068
[SPEAKER_17]: It's silent on that.

251
00:27:46,148 --> 00:27:54,473
[SPEAKER_17]: We were trying to think of a way that you could create an incentive for owner occupancy, but it got very complicated very fast.

252
00:27:54,534 --> 00:28:01,578
[SPEAKER_17]: So we're thinking that zoning is unfortunately for I think the people who brought it up, it's not the appropriate level.

253
00:28:02,138 --> 00:28:03,699
[SPEAKER_17]: or the appropriate place for it.

254
00:28:04,319 --> 00:28:14,224
[SPEAKER_17]: Hiring local companies, I have seen as part of, for example, if it's city owned property, it's part of the land disposition agreement.

255
00:28:14,324 --> 00:28:18,246
[SPEAKER_17]: It's not usually something that, it's not something I've seen in zoning itself.

256
00:28:18,947 --> 00:28:26,551
[SPEAKER_17]: So I believe I have also, although it's been a while, I've seen city ordinances to that effect that are non-zoning ordinances.

257
00:28:26,631 --> 00:28:28,912
[SPEAKER_17]: So unfortunately we don't think zoning is the right place.

258
00:28:29,753 --> 00:28:34,698
[SPEAKER_17]: And then the remediation of the soil and industrial areas came up when talking about residential.

259
00:28:34,758 --> 00:28:45,850
[SPEAKER_17]: There is already a requirement that if a residential use is going on a former industrial site, it under a mass environmental law has to be remediated to a certain standard.

260
00:28:45,991 --> 00:28:48,774
[SPEAKER_17]: So that's kind of baked into that use.

261
00:28:49,654 --> 00:29:03,581
[SPEAKER_17]: We do recognize that that is an issue, but it may be that the existing Massachusetts laws for remediation are probably going to override anything in the zoning.

262
00:29:03,701 --> 00:29:16,186
[SPEAKER_17]: So just, we're happy to look into any of these further if so directed, but our initial thought was that unfortunately zoning either doesn't address it or it's addressed elsewhere in the law.

263
00:29:17,567 --> 00:29:19,448
[SPEAKER_17]: And with that, I am going to stop.

264
00:29:19,488 --> 00:29:22,890
[SPEAKER_17]: I'll just note for anybody who might have come in, because I can't see who's behind us now.

265
00:29:22,950 --> 00:29:27,792
[SPEAKER_17]: If you came in later, we do have copies of the maps up here at the front.

266
00:29:27,832 --> 00:29:29,453
[SPEAKER_17]: And of course, we have the boards in the back.

267
00:29:30,273 --> 00:29:35,775
[SPEAKER_17]: And I'm going to stop sharing and turn it back to Council President Behrs.

