490
00:50:55,101 --> 00:50:57,982
[SPEAKER_20]: Do we have any further questions or comments from members of the Council?

491
00:50:58,022 --> 00:50:58,922
[SPEAKER_20]: Councillor Callahan.

492
00:51:01,348 --> 00:51:01,648
[SPEAKER_30]: Thanks.

493
00:51:01,929 --> 00:51:03,931
[SPEAKER_30]: I'm just going to adjust so I can read.

494
00:51:04,291 --> 00:51:10,898
[SPEAKER_30]: I actually want to read a comment from someone and it's about a very it's one of the definitions.

495
00:51:10,938 --> 00:51:19,287
[SPEAKER_30]: So I think it will apply citywide and a little bit of context just I don't know how much you guys know about the home sharing proposal which I'm

496
00:51:20,528 --> 00:51:31,797
[SPEAKER_30]: sort of leading, it's a wonderful, it's a great solution for other cities that have many of the same demographic issues and housing issues that we have.

497
00:51:32,918 --> 00:51:36,601
[SPEAKER_30]: We have a larger proportion of seniors than we've ever had before.

498
00:51:36,641 --> 00:51:40,724
[SPEAKER_30]: It's about 24% of the population, I think, don't quote me, that's about right.

499
00:51:42,005 --> 00:51:47,289
[SPEAKER_30]: And many of them live in homes that are, there's either one or two people living in a home that has four or five or six bedrooms.

500
00:51:48,330 --> 00:52:11,603
[SPEAKER_30]: And home sharing is a wonderful way to help them stay in their homes longer, get a little bit of a discount on their mortgage, and get a little help around the house as they age by sort of handholding and matchmaking them with a younger person who is looking for a housing situation and can help them around the house.

501
00:52:12,543 --> 00:52:26,852
[SPEAKER_30]: So the reason I give you some context is I'm looking at page 12 under accessory uses number 7 and it says renting of one or two rooms without separate cooking facilities to lodgers within a dwelling unit to one or two total lodgers.

502
00:52:27,133 --> 00:52:30,395
[SPEAKER_30]: And so that is pretty much what the home sharing will be.

503
00:52:31,516 --> 00:52:32,837
[SPEAKER_30]: It'll fall into that category.

504
00:52:33,317 --> 00:52:42,207
[SPEAKER_30]: And so the person who wrote this email, I don't think she minds that I'm sharing that it's Roberta Cameron who is helping with the home sharing project.

505
00:52:42,988 --> 00:52:49,755
[SPEAKER_30]: She says, in the table of uses, I believe strongly that we should not be mandating parking for renting bedrooms to one or two lodgers.

506
00:52:50,242 --> 00:52:54,405
[SPEAKER_30]: Renting rooms to lodgers is an important component of our naturally affordable housing supply.

507
00:52:54,806 --> 00:52:59,990
[SPEAKER_30]: Since these rooms are often rented well below market rates, it can help to offset housing costs for lower income homeowners.

508
00:53:00,550 --> 00:53:07,976
[SPEAKER_30]: The boundary between lodgers and other household members can be porous, as they may be care providers, friends or family, exchange students or guests for any length of time.

509
00:53:08,496 --> 00:53:16,062
[SPEAKER_30]: Most importantly, having at least a decade of experience with guest household members who are typically working adults myself,

510
00:53:17,457 --> 00:53:21,921
[SPEAKER_30]: She says, the vast majority of people who occupy rooms do not have cars.

511
00:53:22,521 --> 00:53:30,068
[SPEAKER_30]: The requirement to provide an off-street parking space to lodgers will eliminate the choice of many individual homeowners to share their extra rooms.

512
00:53:30,748 --> 00:53:36,093
[SPEAKER_30]: Homeowners and prospective lodgers can assess whether the availability of pavement surrounding their property is appropriate to meet their needs,

513
00:53:36,633 --> 00:53:39,698
[SPEAKER_30]: or if they would prefer to have a garden, a tree, or space for their vehicle.

514
00:53:40,218 --> 00:53:43,443
[SPEAKER_30]: And they can decide accordingly whether the available arrangement will work for them.

515
00:53:44,224 --> 00:53:51,074
[SPEAKER_30]: When we should be reducing barriers to housing diversity, this measure is needlessly creating a new barrier without solving a problem.

516
00:53:51,595 --> 00:53:56,476
[SPEAKER_30]: She does also add, aside from this, I'm supportive of the proposed zoning for the Postman Ave corridor as is.

517
00:53:56,496 --> 00:54:03,377
[SPEAKER_30]: I think it strikes the right balance, although I would like to ensure that we have strong and lasting public benefits as incentives for greater diversity.

518
00:54:03,757 --> 00:54:20,520
[SPEAKER_30]: So I just wanted to bring that up and make a suggestion that as we consider parking requirements, that we do consider lodgers differently from how we consider other sort of by per unit parking requirements around the city.

519
00:54:20,640 --> 00:54:20,880
[SPEAKER_30]: Thank you.

520
00:54:24,520 --> 00:54:26,789
[SPEAKER_20]: Thank you, Councilor, oh, Councilor Malauulu.

521
00:54:28,522 --> 00:54:28,962
[SPEAKER_27]: Thank you.

522
00:54:29,802 --> 00:54:35,603
[SPEAKER_27]: And thank you again for all of the different diagrams and ways of breaking this down to kind of see some of the changes in here.

523
00:54:36,363 --> 00:54:45,945
[SPEAKER_27]: One of the questions I had was, I know you showed it on the screen as well, but I think I was the one a couple of meetings back that brought back up the drive-through for the pharmacy.

524
00:54:47,326 --> 00:54:54,567
[SPEAKER_27]: I think, you know, some of the comments about allowing for seniors to have access to it, that it's easier for them to not have to get out of the car, et cetera.

525
00:54:55,027 --> 00:54:56,208
[SPEAKER_27]: to be able to have that drive-through.

526
00:54:56,228 --> 00:55:00,570
[SPEAKER_27]: I could only, I was trying to see if I, I didn't think I saw it within the pack.

527
00:55:00,610 --> 00:55:23,141
[SPEAKER_27]: I was trying to read it quickly, but in terms of the feasibility that you're seeing in that area, do you mind just kind of sharing again, like, your thoughts on it or what else needs to be done to see how much of a traffic, because I'm not trying, certainly not trying to create more traffic, but I do hear the need of people aren't not able to, you know, get out of their car and utilizing the drive-through.

528
00:55:24,482 --> 00:55:27,723
[SPEAKER_27]: I just wanted to see if you could just share a little bit more feedback on that.

529
00:55:33,886 --> 00:55:36,006
[SPEAKER_17]: So, thank you, counselor.

530
00:55:36,106 --> 00:55:45,770
[SPEAKER_17]: It was interesting, I was mentioning this to somebody else the other day who's a parent of a young child and she said, oh yes, drive-through pharmacies, please.

531
00:55:46,230 --> 00:55:50,432
[SPEAKER_17]: Not a Bedford resident, we were talking about a different zoning proposal but,

532
00:55:51,352 --> 00:56:05,056
[SPEAKER_17]: So it was interesting going back and looking at which standards would apply to a drive-through pharmacy because a lot of the standards were more focused on fast food retail.

533
00:56:05,757 --> 00:56:16,900
[SPEAKER_17]: So I had talked with Director Hunt about the issue of queuing and how that is likely to have the largest traffic impact because of it spilling out.

534
00:56:17,540 --> 00:56:19,883
[SPEAKER_17]: So I'll go through the recommendation.

535
00:56:20,264 --> 00:56:28,994
[SPEAKER_17]: This is obviously a draft and so any pharmacy that's going to have a drive-through obviously has to meet the other parking requirements.

536
00:56:30,115 --> 00:56:36,983
[SPEAKER_17]: Right now I have suggested that it just be no more than one combined teller and pickup window.

537
00:56:37,603 --> 00:56:51,528
[SPEAKER_17]: is allowed unless they can show good cause for separating those windows into two windows and they would have to make that case to the community development board who would then allow for a single teller window with a single pickup window.

538
00:56:52,969 --> 00:57:00,912
[SPEAKER_17]: Window locations would have to be or shall be located to minimize the impact of direct glare from headlights in the queue.

539
00:57:01,532 --> 00:57:05,835
[SPEAKER_17]: on residential properties that are in line of sight from the queuing lane.

540
00:57:06,376 --> 00:57:09,718
[SPEAKER_17]: A minimum of three queue spaces is required per window.

541
00:57:09,758 --> 00:57:12,080
[SPEAKER_17]: I found that standard in a couple of places.

542
00:57:13,101 --> 00:57:21,187
[SPEAKER_17]: Dimensions for queue spaces have to be at least 10 feet in width and 20 feet in length so that there's a defined standard for those three spaces.

543
00:57:22,247 --> 00:57:29,390
[SPEAKER_17]: Each queue lane has to be clearly defined, designated so as not to conflict or interfere with other pedestrian or vehicular traffic.

544
00:57:30,290 --> 00:57:39,274
[SPEAKER_17]: The stacking area shall not be located adjacent and parallel to a street or public right of way unless the review authority determines that there's no feasible alternative.

545
00:57:39,794 --> 00:57:44,636
[SPEAKER_17]: That obviously would be the CD board for a site because this would come up for a site plan review.

546
00:57:45,536 --> 00:57:56,562
[SPEAKER_17]: And then signs, the entrance and exits have to be clearly marked to show the direction of traffic flows by signs, pavement markings, and raised curbs.

547
00:57:57,122 --> 00:58:03,005
[SPEAKER_17]: So as I was pulling a bunch of the different standards together, it's how do you keep the cars off the street?

548
00:58:03,425 --> 00:58:08,508
[SPEAKER_17]: How do you minimize the impact of pedestrians and vehicular traffic?

549
00:58:08,908 --> 00:58:12,870
[SPEAKER_17]: How do you separate those people who are parking from those people who are going through the drive-through?

550
00:58:13,450 --> 00:58:19,936
[SPEAKER_17]: There was one section on accessibility standards for Windows, for ADA compliance for Windows.

551
00:58:20,416 --> 00:58:29,664
[SPEAKER_17]: That seemed to be covered by other industry standards and other ADA requirements, so I didn't put it in here, but it's certainly something to think about.

552
00:58:29,744 --> 00:58:35,790
[SPEAKER_17]: I don't know if any of you have ever driven up to, say, a drive-through bank and you're in completely the wrong car.

553
00:58:37,431 --> 00:58:41,475
[SPEAKER_17]: for the facility that they put you either in the car that's too high or the car that's too low.

554
00:58:41,936 --> 00:58:55,649
[SPEAKER_17]: So we might consider, given that one of the populations for a drive-through pharmacy window are people who do have limited mobility, we might consider adding that as a standard as well, just as kind of a belt and suspenders.

555
00:58:55,769 --> 00:58:59,513
[SPEAKER_17]: But those are the issues that I was thinking about as I pulled those together.

556
00:59:00,064 --> 00:59:00,144
[SPEAKER_27]: OK.

557
00:59:00,444 --> 00:59:00,744
[SPEAKER_27]: Thank you.

558
00:59:00,784 --> 00:59:01,265
[SPEAKER_27]: I appreciate it.

559
00:59:01,285 --> 00:59:05,487
[SPEAKER_27]: I just wanted to I appreciate you taking the time to look through those different aspects of it.

560
00:59:05,888 --> 00:59:20,777
[SPEAKER_27]: And I guess in terms of how you decide or how you figure out what kind of impact that would be traffic wise is it just what you know or have seen in other areas or how exactly do you determine if having a drive through like that would impact that area as much.

561
00:59:21,110 --> 00:59:27,419
[SPEAKER_17]: That's going to have to be on a development by development case and they're going to have to show that as part of their application.

562
00:59:27,479 --> 00:59:37,314
[SPEAKER_17]: Just the reason being are we talking about a pharmacy that's on a corner with one busy street and one quiet street is a pharmacy located mid block on a busier street.

563
00:59:38,134 --> 00:59:40,335
[SPEAKER_17]: What is the configuration of the entrances?

564
00:59:40,435 --> 00:59:44,356
[SPEAKER_17]: So that I think is, that would have to be site by site.

565
00:59:44,436 --> 00:59:48,718
[SPEAKER_17]: It would otherwise be too difficult to make assumptions about that.

566
00:59:49,098 --> 00:59:56,520
[SPEAKER_17]: But I think the queuing factor in the discussions was the highest, but get, those cars should not be stacked up on the street.

567
00:59:56,920 --> 00:59:58,321
[SPEAKER_17]: So that was the biggest piece.

568
00:59:58,761 --> 00:59:59,921
[SPEAKER_27]: Okay, thank you, I appreciate it.

569
01:00:00,301 --> 01:00:00,861
[SPEAKER_17]: You're very welcome.

570
01:00:03,062 --> 01:00:03,442
[SPEAKER_20]: Thank you.

571
01:00:03,502 --> 01:00:06,063
[SPEAKER_20]: Any further questions or comments by members of the council at this time?

572
01:00:09,825 --> 01:00:11,186
[SPEAKER_20]: Seeing none, I'll turn it over to you, Chair Carr.

573
01:00:16,609 --> 01:00:24,854
[SPEAKER_07]: All right, before I start talking about with the various board members, I have a brief presentation I'd like to give.

574
01:00:25,495 --> 01:00:28,456
[SPEAKER_07]: Just some of my thoughts so they have some graphic quality to them.

575
01:00:28,577 --> 01:00:37,222
[SPEAKER_07]: I have some photos and some pieces of the zoning that I'd like to share with people to explain my perspective on this.

576
01:00:39,668 --> 01:00:39,768
Oops.

577
01:00:48,728 --> 01:00:48,969
[SPEAKER_07]: Okay.

578
01:00:51,031 --> 01:00:52,651
[SPEAKER_07]: So a couple of early comments.

579
01:00:53,072 --> 01:00:58,553
[SPEAKER_07]: I really appreciate that this plan goes back a couple of years far before I was on the board.

580
01:00:58,613 --> 01:01:03,795
[SPEAKER_07]: But I think I have some fundamental disagreements with a lot of pieces of this plan.

581
01:01:03,815 --> 01:01:07,016
[SPEAKER_07]: And I'm going to go through a couple of sites and go through them.

582
01:01:07,616 --> 01:01:13,598
[SPEAKER_07]: Because I feel like we just had a very successful effort with the Medford Square zoning.

583
01:01:15,584 --> 01:01:22,810
[SPEAKER_07]: I think that the Salem Street zoning that preceded it, that caused an incredible backlash in the city, was far less successful.

584
01:01:23,110 --> 01:01:35,300
[SPEAKER_07]: And I think the approach to the zoning feels to me closer to Salem Street than it does to what we had in Meffitt Square, even though a lot of things in Meffitt Square are here, but some things are not, and I think they need to be.

585
01:01:37,001 --> 01:01:43,584
[SPEAKER_07]: One is the commercial boundaries of the proposal are far beyond what's there now.

586
01:01:43,944 --> 01:01:49,307
[SPEAKER_07]: We appear to be trying to extend the commercial boundaries to make more of Boston Ave a commercial zone.

587
01:01:49,527 --> 01:01:59,132
[SPEAKER_07]: Every time there's a store on a piece of a lot, we tend to grab some three or four houses around it and zone them up to what that store is so that we can have potentially

588
01:02:00,235 --> 01:02:05,856
[SPEAKER_07]: a bigger building at some point or a more commercial zone with more shops, more height, et cetera.

589
01:02:05,956 --> 01:02:12,258
[SPEAKER_07]: I just don't agree with that approach in a significant number of spaces along the corridor.

590
01:02:13,178 --> 01:02:15,619
[SPEAKER_07]: The second is that I think the heights are simply too tall.

591
01:02:16,379 --> 01:02:21,100
[SPEAKER_07]: When I look at BA2 and BA3, they really impact the character

592
01:02:21,622 --> 01:02:24,243
[SPEAKER_07]: of Boston Avenue, the character of the neighborhoods around them.

593
01:02:26,183 --> 01:02:32,164
[SPEAKER_07]: There's a lot of two-family houses that have been there for 100 years that will be really negatively impacted by this.

594
01:02:32,204 --> 01:02:34,825
[SPEAKER_07]: And I'll show some examples when I get to it.

595
01:02:35,625 --> 01:02:40,966
[SPEAKER_07]: B3 is one that is really troublesome for me because it's 98 feet at a maximum number with incentives.

596
01:02:41,906 --> 01:02:48,368
[SPEAKER_07]: That is only nine feet less than the Tufts dorm that's being built right now, which is universally described by

597
01:02:49,800 --> 01:02:55,048
[SPEAKER_07]: hundreds of people I've met, as the worst building they've seen in Medford, a complete disaster for Hillside.

598
01:02:56,130 --> 01:03:00,737
[SPEAKER_07]: We couldn't stop Tufts from doing it, but we should not do it to ourselves.

599
01:03:01,418 --> 01:03:02,619
[SPEAKER_07]: That's what we should not do.

600
01:03:02,659 --> 01:03:04,482
[SPEAKER_07]: And 98 feet to me is a bridge too far.

601
01:03:10,351 --> 01:03:12,612
[SPEAKER_07]: I want to talk a little bit about neighborhood quality and impact.

602
01:03:14,032 --> 01:03:16,913
[SPEAKER_07]: There are a lot of places where we should just leave houses as they are.

603
01:03:17,613 --> 01:03:24,196
[SPEAKER_07]: There's houses along Boston Ave, triple deckers, seven in a row that just, there's no reason to change them.

604
01:03:25,196 --> 01:03:34,639
[SPEAKER_07]: And there's also houses that go back off Boston Ave that are on Hillsdale and Adams, but they're being rezoned and that would change the character of those neighborhoods.

605
01:03:34,679 --> 01:03:37,120
[SPEAKER_07]: And I think people who buy houses in those neighborhoods

606
01:03:37,874 --> 01:03:39,136
[SPEAKER_07]: don't want to live on Boston Ave.

607
01:03:39,796 --> 01:03:43,260
[SPEAKER_07]: And I feel like they're almost being forced to do that with the new zoning.

608
01:03:43,300 --> 01:03:47,245
[SPEAKER_07]: They're being kind of put in that Boston Ave bucket where I don't think they belong.

609
01:03:47,285 --> 01:03:48,847
[SPEAKER_07]: I think this was true on Salem Street.

610
01:03:49,507 --> 01:03:56,075
[SPEAKER_07]: And I think we have to go back to Salem Street and remove some of those properties because I think some of those neighborhoods should be left as they are.

611
01:03:57,832 --> 01:04:00,854
[SPEAKER_07]: Let me jump ahead to a couple of examples.

612
01:04:01,015 --> 01:04:05,198
[SPEAKER_07]: What I'm proposing is really a little bit different.

613
01:04:07,459 --> 01:04:17,806
[SPEAKER_07]: BA1, I'm saying go four stories, 50 feet, with one to get to 60 feet, because I think in many of the cases where that occurs, it's actually a reasonable scale.

614
01:04:18,675 --> 01:04:19,996
[SPEAKER_07]: because of what's around the neighborhood.

615
01:04:20,136 --> 01:04:32,402
[SPEAKER_07]: But on BA2 and BA3, I'm saying limit it not to 86 feet, but to 70 feet, because 70 feet is just at the point where it becomes a high rise and where wood frame becomes very expensive to build.

616
01:04:33,102 --> 01:04:35,423
[SPEAKER_07]: You're not going to have a lot of steel buildings on this site.

617
01:04:35,443 --> 01:04:39,665
[SPEAKER_07]: You're going to have some podium buildings, one or two floors of parking with retail on the ground.

618
01:04:40,252 --> 01:04:42,513
[SPEAKER_07]: and then four or five stories of wood frame above.

619
01:04:42,573 --> 01:04:45,335
[SPEAKER_07]: That's what the sphere building is, which we looked at earlier.

620
01:04:45,355 --> 01:04:47,596
[SPEAKER_07]: That's a great model for a lot of this corridor.

621
01:04:47,616 --> 01:04:54,540
[SPEAKER_07]: So I'm proposing that BA2 get maxed out at 70 feet and BA3 85 feet max.

622
01:04:55,020 --> 01:05:06,447
[SPEAKER_07]: And it's really critical that these are not on Boston Ave, that they step back from Boston Ave, that they're not 85 feet on Boston Ave, but they're 85 feet by the railroad tracks where

623
01:05:07,126 --> 01:05:13,531
[SPEAKER_07]: I don't think the commuter rail trains care if it's an 85-foot building, but they do care on Boston Ave a lot.

624
01:05:16,974 --> 01:05:22,117
[SPEAKER_07]: So let's talk about, I just mentioned that what I'm looking for change in BA3.

625
01:05:23,579 --> 01:05:30,204
[SPEAKER_07]: I'm glad to hear what Alicia said, because I certainly agree with it, that we want to remove Walkling Court completely from this proposal.

626
01:05:30,224 --> 01:05:32,185
[SPEAKER_07]: You can see the rendering on the left side.

627
01:05:32,966 --> 01:05:35,147
[SPEAKER_07]: I view that as a really successful zoning.

628
01:05:36,068 --> 01:05:42,809
[SPEAKER_07]: Six stories along the railroad tracks, four stories in the middle, three story townhouses, then you have residential buildings.

629
01:05:42,829 --> 01:05:44,070
[SPEAKER_07]: It's a perfect step up.

630
01:05:44,730 --> 01:05:47,170
[SPEAKER_07]: We shouldn't do anything to it because it's a good design.

631
01:05:47,190 --> 01:05:50,331
[SPEAKER_07]: It hasn't even been built yet, so let's leave it as is.

632
01:05:50,771 --> 01:05:57,352
[SPEAKER_07]: And I think there's a strong feeling with some people, obviously the planning board believes it as well.

633
01:05:57,872 --> 01:06:00,913
[SPEAKER_07]: I think some of the people on the city board will also agree to that.

634
01:06:02,283 --> 01:06:05,825
[SPEAKER_07]: These are the Boston Ave, Winthrop Street, Topeka Street.

635
01:06:05,845 --> 01:06:17,233
[SPEAKER_07]: These are the seven triple-decker houses that are being proposed to be zoned so that they could be up to 50 feet tall, I think four stories in the base zoning.

636
01:06:17,853 --> 01:06:23,237
[SPEAKER_07]: Again, I mean, these buildings are solid, really dense housing.

637
01:06:24,558 --> 01:06:27,840
[SPEAKER_07]: I don't think you can have a continuous retail along Boston Ave.

638
01:06:27,860 --> 01:06:29,301
[SPEAKER_07]: I don't think there's the foot traffic for it.

639
01:06:29,321 --> 01:06:30,582
[SPEAKER_07]: I don't think there's the demand for it.

640
01:06:31,127 --> 01:06:36,171
[SPEAKER_07]: I like to focus the retail where it is and build it higher and better than it is now.

641
01:06:37,673 --> 01:06:46,420
[SPEAKER_07]: And that's really, you know, where the church is, where the apartment building is, the three-story apartment building, all the way to the Danish coffee house, all the way to Nick's Pizza.

642
01:06:47,080 --> 01:06:50,343
[SPEAKER_07]: All those buildings could be four or five stories tall and I think it would be great.

643
01:06:51,524 --> 01:06:55,748
[SPEAKER_07]: Improved retail, more shops, more restaurants, more people living above them.

644
01:06:56,726 --> 01:07:02,831
[SPEAKER_07]: But I don't think taking the houses around these areas are the right approach.

645
01:07:03,851 --> 01:07:10,176
[SPEAKER_07]: These are the seven, or I think it's seven or eight, three families that I think we should just leave alone.

646
01:07:10,196 --> 01:07:14,239
[SPEAKER_07]: Let's see.

647
01:07:15,941 --> 01:07:21,585
[SPEAKER_07]: Yeah, again, this is just more of the same with the houses that are really on the side streets from Hillsdale and Adams being part of it.

648
01:07:22,933 --> 01:07:24,273
[SPEAKER_07]: Moving to the south now.

649
01:07:25,134 --> 01:07:27,014
[SPEAKER_07]: Again, this is a great new building that was built.

650
01:07:28,274 --> 01:07:32,496
[SPEAKER_07]: Four stories of wood frame over one story of a little bit retail and parking underneath.

651
01:07:34,156 --> 01:07:35,617
[SPEAKER_07]: This is zoned for 85 feet.

652
01:07:35,657 --> 01:07:37,557
[SPEAKER_07]: This building is only 55 feet.

653
01:07:38,137 --> 01:07:40,218
[SPEAKER_07]: Imagine that building with three more stories.

654
01:07:40,278 --> 01:07:44,059
[SPEAKER_07]: It's a really big impact on the houses across the street.

655
01:07:44,599 --> 01:07:45,319
[SPEAKER_07]: Five is a lot.

656
01:07:45,899 --> 01:07:47,700
[SPEAKER_07]: Eight is, in my opinion, a bridge too far.

657
01:07:49,109 --> 01:07:52,932
[SPEAKER_07]: So I think 5 over 1, 4 over 1, those are good buildings.

658
01:07:54,133 --> 01:07:55,634
[SPEAKER_07]: And the next two are the St.

659
01:07:55,654 --> 01:07:58,576
[SPEAKER_07]: Clements sites that I'm proposing we add to the zoning.

660
01:07:58,616 --> 01:07:59,717
[SPEAKER_07]: I'm not against zoning.

661
01:07:59,757 --> 01:08:01,198
[SPEAKER_07]: I want to just put it in the right place.

662
01:08:01,278 --> 01:08:04,180
[SPEAKER_07]: This is the St.

663
01:08:04,360 --> 01:08:05,001
[SPEAKER_07]: Clements High School.

664
01:08:05,021 --> 01:08:05,801
[SPEAKER_07]: This is in the zoning.

665
01:08:06,382 --> 01:08:10,965
[SPEAKER_07]: But again, we're talking about a potential for an, I think it's an 85 foot,

666
01:08:12,828 --> 01:08:14,650
[SPEAKER_07]: tall building on this site.

667
01:08:15,090 --> 01:08:18,493
[SPEAKER_07]: That's a 35 to 40 story 40 foot tall building.

668
01:08:19,273 --> 01:08:21,455
[SPEAKER_07]: You have to almost more than double it.

669
01:08:22,396 --> 01:08:28,661
[SPEAKER_07]: And for the people who live on Saint Clemens Road, right along the edge here, like their world now is a sheer wall.

670
01:08:29,201 --> 01:08:29,842
[SPEAKER_07]: And I just think

671
01:08:31,584 --> 01:08:32,264
[SPEAKER_07]: There's a better way.

672
01:08:32,304 --> 01:08:33,686
[SPEAKER_07]: We can add a few floors to this building.

673
01:08:33,726 --> 01:08:41,453
[SPEAKER_07]: This building needs to be redeveloped into more housing, but I think it's too tall.

674
01:08:41,593 --> 01:08:50,802
[SPEAKER_07]: So I'm proposing that it goes to BA1, which could be, again, four stories with a little incentive for historic to maybe go to five stories.

675
01:08:50,902 --> 01:08:55,407
[SPEAKER_07]: You can build on top of that building, build two more floors, and I think nobody would blink an eye at it.

676
01:08:56,885 --> 01:08:57,345
[SPEAKER_07]: Same thing.

677
01:08:57,405 --> 01:09:00,706
[SPEAKER_07]: This is the building that was not in the zoning.

678
01:09:00,726 --> 01:09:04,467
[SPEAKER_07]: The other one was, excuse me, the previous one, but this is the St.

679
01:09:04,507 --> 01:09:05,668
[SPEAKER_07]: Clemens Elementary School.

680
01:09:06,968 --> 01:09:07,948
[SPEAKER_07]: Again, three stories.

681
01:09:08,969 --> 01:09:13,510
[SPEAKER_07]: Again, I think we can go at least another story, maybe two, up to 50 feet, maybe a little bit more.

682
01:09:14,410 --> 01:09:16,811
[SPEAKER_07]: And the rectory next to it is the same thing.

683
01:09:17,291 --> 01:09:18,732
[SPEAKER_07]: That's all one big campus.

684
01:09:18,772 --> 01:09:22,353
[SPEAKER_07]: I think there's a development opportunity there, which makes sense, but it needs to be,

685
01:09:23,353 --> 01:09:28,276
[SPEAKER_07]: sensitive to its neighbors, and its neighbors not just who abut it, but who are across the street from it as well.

686
01:09:28,336 --> 01:09:31,038
[SPEAKER_07]: Those neighbors need to be thought of in the same way.

687
01:09:32,018 --> 01:09:34,680
[SPEAKER_07]: So those are my big picture comments.

688
01:09:34,900 --> 01:09:41,824
[SPEAKER_07]: I don't know how anyone on the council or even the city board feel about these because I just distributed them to Mark yesterday.

