[SPEAKER_16]: Sorry.

846
01:21:24,549 --> 01:21:30,432
[SPEAKER_24]: So I actually just want to share with you right now one of there's a case that's been going through the ZBA.

847
01:21:31,653 --> 01:21:37,936
[SPEAKER_24]: And what it is is that in a residential neighborhood in Medford people had started a gutter business.

848
01:21:38,516 --> 01:21:43,819
[SPEAKER_24]: And now that gutter business is loading and unloading their trucks in the morning next to people's homes.

849
01:21:44,580 --> 01:21:47,121
[SPEAKER_24]: And it's really disruptive to the neighbors.

850
01:21:47,561 --> 01:21:49,622
[SPEAKER_24]: And so they've come out and said this isn't allowed.

851
01:21:49,662 --> 01:21:51,063
[SPEAKER_24]: This is not a home business.

852
01:21:51,503 --> 01:21:52,544
[SPEAKER_24]: This shouldn't be okay.

853
01:21:52,944 --> 01:22:03,752
[SPEAKER_24]: And so trying to hit the balance where you might actually be back up against homes of something that has the potential to be noisy versus something that is not.

854
01:22:03,832 --> 01:22:05,053
[SPEAKER_24]: And how do you control that?

855
01:22:05,093 --> 01:22:14,981
[SPEAKER_24]: And I think that when we went through the list, like our gut instinct is that a plumbing place could be noisy, loading and unloading trucks and stuff.

856
01:22:16,362 --> 01:22:28,851
[SPEAKER_24]: Now, in theory, anybody can be noisy because you can have your trash emptied and you have dumpsters and your trucks back up, so anything can be noisy, but versus the like, by definition is part of the work.

857
01:22:29,371 --> 01:22:34,895
[SPEAKER_24]: Now, if somebody wants to teach us that plumbings are not, I don't actually know.

858
01:22:34,915 --> 01:22:36,236
[SPEAKER_24]: Nobody's complained about one of them.

859
01:22:36,676 --> 01:22:41,780
[SPEAKER_24]: I just wanted to share that there's actually a case like that going through the ZBA right now.

860
01:22:45,810 --> 01:22:46,330
[SPEAKER_16]: That's fair.

861
01:22:46,350 --> 01:22:47,711
[SPEAKER_16]: I agree with that.

862
01:22:49,011 --> 01:23:02,017
[SPEAKER_16]: The other thing that I think we should consider is I think it was May 13th we saw a proposal to add another type of residential use to the table.

863
01:23:02,157 --> 01:23:06,820
[SPEAKER_16]: And I think it's purpose built student housing which is a totally different concept.

864
01:23:07,760 --> 01:23:16,126
[SPEAKER_16]: than the, what is it, 107-story, 107-feet building that's at the top of Tufts University.

865
01:23:16,146 --> 01:23:21,310
[SPEAKER_16]: And believe me, I walk Boston Avenue almost every day.

866
01:23:21,330 --> 01:23:29,676
[SPEAKER_16]: I go by Nick's Pizza and I go by Temper and all that, and I just look in amazement like a minion at the size of that mammoth building.

867
01:23:30,276 --> 01:23:46,292
[SPEAKER_16]: But I do think that we could include some type of residential student housing that is privately owned, that is scaled appropriately to the zoning in the need in the area.

868
01:23:46,812 --> 01:23:50,074
[SPEAKER_16]: and will also generate tax revenue for the city.

869
01:23:51,014 --> 01:24:08,282
[SPEAKER_16]: I do feel that I agree that students do not require cars, as many as the residents, and I strongly feel that with some additional student housing for Tufts University, they will pull some of the students from the surrounding neighborhoods.

870
01:24:09,082 --> 01:24:22,812
[SPEAKER_16]: Just alone in my street, I have seen two family houses that have been redeveloped beautifully the first time, wonderful houses redeveloped, pristine lawns, perfect trash cans.

871
01:24:22,852 --> 01:24:23,592
[SPEAKER_16]: But what happens?

872
01:24:24,013 --> 01:24:25,674
[SPEAKER_16]: You get an absentee landlord.

873
01:24:26,214 --> 01:24:27,675
[SPEAKER_16]: The absentee landlord leaves.

874
01:24:29,056 --> 01:24:30,539
[SPEAKER_16]: It is occupied by students.

875
01:24:31,200 --> 01:24:32,944
[SPEAKER_16]: They're transient populations.

876
01:24:33,324 --> 01:24:34,747
[SPEAKER_16]: They're not part of the community.

877
01:24:34,787 --> 01:24:35,569
[SPEAKER_16]: They're really not.

878
01:24:35,589 --> 01:24:37,412
[SPEAKER_16]: They're here for a couple of years.

879
01:24:37,472 --> 01:24:38,013
[SPEAKER_16]: They leave.

880
01:24:38,614 --> 01:24:40,398
[SPEAKER_16]: We have noise, rats.

881
01:24:41,937 --> 01:24:46,661
[SPEAKER_16]: problems, and people that I have grown up with are gone.

882
01:24:47,062 --> 01:24:51,806
[SPEAKER_16]: And it's really the coziness and the warmth of the area has been lost.

883
01:24:52,367 --> 01:25:04,157
[SPEAKER_16]: And I do think that if there was a concept where we could have student housing, because there's always going to be student housing around the Hillside area, and I know in South Medford, you're not going to get away from it.

884
01:25:04,798 --> 01:25:16,473
[SPEAKER_16]: But if it was done in a way where it was managed appropriately and it fit the need of what was needed in the neighborhood, it wasn't this behemoth 107 foot building.

885
01:25:18,900 --> 01:25:24,583
[SPEAKER_16]: I think it would work, and I think we should give it a try with the right ordinances in place to do that.

886
01:25:25,623 --> 01:25:34,027
[SPEAKER_16]: And regarding traffic, one of the things I have to say about traffic is that, yes, people have cars.

887
01:25:34,648 --> 01:25:36,789
[SPEAKER_16]: People need to drive in and out of Medford.

888
01:25:36,809 --> 01:25:38,489
[SPEAKER_16]: Not everybody can take the train to work.

889
01:25:39,630 --> 01:25:42,651
[SPEAKER_16]: I'm a health surveyor, and I need to take my car.

890
01:25:43,352 --> 01:25:47,174
[SPEAKER_16]: But one of the things with Medford is a problem, and we all know it.

891
01:25:47,974 --> 01:25:49,475
[SPEAKER_16]: is that we're a cut-through city.

892
01:25:50,395 --> 01:25:54,376
[SPEAKER_16]: When I want to go to Route 2, I go down Boston Avenue.

893
01:25:54,636 --> 01:25:55,177
[SPEAKER_16]: I do it.

894
01:25:55,497 --> 01:25:55,957
[SPEAKER_16]: I do it.

895
01:25:56,057 --> 01:25:56,657
[SPEAKER_16]: I cut through.

896
01:25:56,677 --> 01:25:57,757
[SPEAKER_16]: I do it all the time.

897
01:25:58,058 --> 01:25:59,418
[SPEAKER_16]: People cut through Meffitt Square.

898
01:26:00,038 --> 01:26:07,241
[SPEAKER_16]: So the issue with traffic is not only the number of cars that we have, it's the basic cut-through nature of the city that we live in.

899
01:26:08,241 --> 01:26:22,315
[SPEAKER_16]: So I would make the recommendation to add that type of residential use with the correct ordinances in place with the correct registration for the students.

900
01:26:22,455 --> 01:26:27,020
[SPEAKER_16]: I know that there are at least three students that I know.

901
01:26:27,696 --> 01:26:36,748
[SPEAKER_16]: that use driveways in my street, and they go to Northeastern, Suffolk University, and they go to BU.

902
01:26:37,269 --> 01:26:39,973
[SPEAKER_16]: They go up the street, they take the green line.

903
01:26:40,619 --> 01:26:44,982
[SPEAKER_16]: and they go to school and they park their cars in the driveways in my neighborhood.

904
01:26:45,343 --> 01:26:48,125
[SPEAKER_16]: So it isn't just Tufts University that would benefit from it.

905
01:26:48,745 --> 01:26:50,247
[SPEAKER_16]: It would be other students as well.

906
01:26:50,887 --> 01:26:57,232
[SPEAKER_16]: And the benefit that we would get as a city is increased tax revenue, which we desperately need.

907
01:26:57,632 --> 01:27:04,438
[SPEAKER_16]: The 107 story building from Tufts University is not providing any tax revenue to the city at all.

908
01:27:07,176 --> 01:27:18,367
[SPEAKER_16]: The other thing I did like was the incentive on waste management for hazardous materials, hazardous waste remediation.

909
01:27:18,387 --> 01:27:19,608
[SPEAKER_16]: I think it's a really good idea.

910
01:27:20,409 --> 01:27:30,720
[SPEAKER_16]: The other thing that the architect presented at that meeting, which I thought was great, was that it is very difficult to build underground parking garages

911
01:27:31,360 --> 01:27:37,682
[SPEAKER_16]: around the area of the BA3 and any of the hillside area because of the water table.

912
01:27:38,282 --> 01:27:39,703
[SPEAKER_16]: I thought that was a great point.

913
01:27:39,763 --> 01:27:41,043
[SPEAKER_16]: I said I didn't even think of that.

914
01:27:41,063 --> 01:27:42,064
[SPEAKER_16]: I didn't even think of that.

915
01:27:42,144 --> 01:27:43,144
[SPEAKER_16]: Thank God he's here.

916
01:27:43,644 --> 01:27:53,748
[SPEAKER_16]: So I think we should also consider that and some other types of incentives that would be beneficial not only to the developer but also to the

917
01:27:54,408 --> 01:28:01,511
[SPEAKER_16]: the really quaint neighborhood of the hillside that I walk a lot and I've really enjoyed.

918
01:28:02,231 --> 01:28:05,473
[SPEAKER_16]: I loved walking around this time because it wasn't snowing.

919
01:28:07,253 --> 01:28:08,234
[SPEAKER_16]: Thank you for listening to me.

920
01:28:08,994 --> 01:28:09,494
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you, Dina.

