929
01:28:47,545 --> 01:28:47,786
[SPEAKER_20]: All right.

930
01:28:48,006 --> 01:28:49,447
[SPEAKER_20]: So just to make sure it works.

931
01:28:49,807 --> 01:28:53,409
[SPEAKER_20]: Neighborhood medical use office by special permit CDB.

932
01:28:54,190 --> 01:28:54,530
[SPEAKER_16]: Yeah.

933
01:28:55,051 --> 01:28:55,331
[SPEAKER_20]: Got it.

934
01:28:55,611 --> 01:28:56,331
[SPEAKER_16]: Gas stations.

935
01:28:56,672 --> 01:28:56,832
[SPEAKER_16]: Yeah.

936
01:28:57,292 --> 01:29:02,616
[SPEAKER_16]: And then of course I agree with Chairman Carr's discussion on the height changes.

937
01:29:04,017 --> 01:29:05,758
[SPEAKER_20]: And I think I had Doug, I can do yours now too.

938
01:29:06,665 --> 01:29:12,891
[SPEAKER_20]: I had the BA1 remove certain residential properties and change to four base plus one incentive.

939
01:29:13,892 --> 01:29:23,522
[SPEAKER_20]: BA2 add the elementary school and rectory properties, change to four base plus two incentive adjacent to the tracks, four base plus one incentive west of Boston Ave.

940
01:29:24,518 --> 01:29:26,559
[SPEAKER_07]: I think both St.

941
01:29:26,579 --> 01:29:34,701
[SPEAKER_07]: Clement's site and the rectory and the elementary school, I was switching from BA2 to BA1 because... I just wanted to... Sure.

942
01:29:35,281 --> 01:29:37,581
[SPEAKER_20]: So I had that as the 4 plus 1.

943
01:29:37,621 --> 01:29:38,461
[SPEAKER_20]: Gotcha.

944
01:29:38,922 --> 01:29:43,263
[SPEAKER_20]: I think we should talk about that because I think we're using the geographical formatting and we kind of didn't want to...

945
01:29:46,048 --> 01:29:53,112
[SPEAKER_20]: I think now we're saying that the district should be contiguous, so I want to make sure that we, I'm trying to capture the change without necessarily saying it should be a different zone.

946
01:29:53,332 --> 01:29:57,354
[SPEAKER_07]: Yeah, we should, yeah, let's just get the boundaries, I think that's the first step.

947
01:29:57,554 --> 01:29:57,774
[SPEAKER_20]: Yeah.

948
01:29:57,814 --> 01:30:01,976
[SPEAKER_20]: And then BA3, remove walk-in court and change to five base two incentive.

949
01:30:02,156 --> 01:30:02,336
[SPEAKER_20]: Right.

950
01:30:02,736 --> 01:30:03,056
[SPEAKER_07]: Correct.

951
01:30:03,257 --> 01:30:03,757
[SPEAKER_20]: All right, great.

952
01:30:05,998 --> 01:30:13,882
[SPEAKER_07]: Okay, I'm going to go to Ali next online because she tends to be last and we, that's just not fair, so I'm going to unmute you.

953
01:30:15,153 --> 01:30:17,214
[SPEAKER_07]: Ari, can you go ahead?

954
01:30:19,334 --> 01:30:25,255
[SPEAKER_03]: Thank you for recognizing me, and thank you to Innocenco and everyone who's been working on this.

955
01:30:25,836 --> 01:30:28,556
[SPEAKER_03]: I overall like where we are with this plan.

956
01:30:29,516 --> 01:30:31,057
[SPEAKER_03]: A few specific comments.

957
01:30:31,717 --> 01:30:38,639
[SPEAKER_03]: I agree with the removal of Walkland Court, as well as Roberta's comment about lodging parking.

958
01:30:38,659 --> 01:30:41,459
[SPEAKER_03]: I think that that should not have a parking minimum.

959
01:30:41,979 --> 01:30:44,220
[SPEAKER_03]: I'm also interested in allowing more growth at that whole

960
01:30:44,620 --> 01:30:48,202
[SPEAKER_03]: foods parcel, and commend the needed changes about green space.

961
01:30:48,702 --> 01:30:59,448
[SPEAKER_03]: I also agree with the permission and encouragement of well-designed student spaces, including private ones, to move the student population out of the existing housing stock, freeing it up for permanent residents.

962
01:31:01,239 --> 01:31:14,711
[SPEAKER_03]: Moving into some stuff where I'm disagreeing with the previous speakers, I am overall a fan of higher heights, more density, and not as tied to preservation of all old buildings as a chair car.

963
01:31:15,892 --> 01:31:23,099
[SPEAKER_03]: This is a difference between us and I think is an area where there are different opinions around the city and where reasonable people can disagree.

964
01:31:24,560 --> 01:31:31,502
[SPEAKER_03]: I also want to remind everyone that zoning does not mandate changes using the example of those seven triple-deckers.

965
01:31:32,502 --> 01:31:35,763
[SPEAKER_03]: If they're working well for their owners, great, they won't change.

966
01:31:37,304 --> 01:31:43,385
[SPEAKER_03]: We don't even know if they're owned by the same owner, and I assume they're not based on how they look.

967
01:31:43,725 --> 01:31:53,048
[SPEAKER_03]: However, if there is interest in a multi-use taller building, as the city changes, as that area changes with the development of the T Station,

968
01:31:53,548 --> 01:31:57,352
[SPEAKER_03]: With other changes in major parcels.

969
01:31:58,933 --> 01:32:04,698
[SPEAKER_03]: That is something that I think should be an option and that option would go through site plan review.

970
01:32:06,893 --> 01:32:12,176
[SPEAKER_03]: And I think that is a particularly dense area with room for growth of that density.

971
01:32:13,417 --> 01:32:14,898
[SPEAKER_03]: And we're not mandating anything.

972
01:32:14,918 --> 01:32:17,920
[SPEAKER_03]: We are allowing developers and owners this option.

973
01:32:19,101 --> 01:32:32,509
[SPEAKER_03]: And kind of thinking about my personal experience with that exact corridor and even those triple-deckers, I haven't checked the exact numbers, but I did have a friend who lived in a triple-decker on Boston Ave for many years as a renter.

974
01:32:33,109 --> 01:32:39,873
[SPEAKER_03]: In kind of 20s and 30s young professional, and it was not great rental and.

975
01:32:40,514 --> 01:32:47,658
[SPEAKER_03]: There was not the opportunity pricing wise or housing stock wise for young professionals to live on their own or with 1 other person.

976
01:32:47,678 --> 01:32:51,781
[SPEAKER_03]: I think allowing redevelopment where it's called for.

977
01:32:53,010 --> 01:33:03,622
[SPEAKER_03]: Allows for increased density of smaller units as well as an increased commercial space and freeze up larger houses and larger units for folks who want them.

978
01:33:04,643 --> 01:33:07,706
[SPEAKER_03]: I think that this increased density is.

979
01:33:09,347 --> 01:33:10,709
[SPEAKER_03]: appropriate for this area.

980
01:33:10,849 --> 01:33:15,416
[SPEAKER_03]: I'm happy to, for us to kind of be looking at some of these specific boundaries.

981
01:33:16,678 --> 01:33:22,787
[SPEAKER_03]: But overall, I think we do have the capacity and desire for that growth.

982
01:33:23,267 --> 01:33:23,528
[SPEAKER_03]: Thank you.

983
01:33:28,998 --> 01:33:30,259
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you, Ari, I appreciate it.

984
01:33:30,479 --> 01:33:41,485
[SPEAKER_07]: I just want to make one comment about historical because you mentioned it and I forgot to mention in my comments and I appreciate that not everyone, even on this board, agrees on every subject all the time.

985
01:33:42,285 --> 01:33:50,830
[SPEAKER_07]: There are actually no buildings north of Winthrop Street in the north zoning area that I think the Historical Commission

986
01:33:51,550 --> 01:33:55,654
[SPEAKER_07]: which I still sit on, would put as preserved.

987
01:33:56,095 --> 01:33:58,718
[SPEAKER_07]: There's so many in Meffitt Square that we're definitely going to do that.

988
01:33:59,375 --> 01:34:01,877
[SPEAKER_07]: But I don't think there's a single one in the north.

989
01:34:01,917 --> 01:34:02,538
[SPEAKER_07]: And I think St.

990
01:34:02,558 --> 01:34:07,902
[SPEAKER_07]: Clement's School, both the high school and the other one, I think they would be in that historical bucket.

991
01:34:08,603 --> 01:34:16,850
[SPEAKER_07]: But by and large, most of this district, 90 plus percent of it, in my opinion, does not have a lot of historical character that we would care about.

992
01:34:17,490 --> 01:34:21,614
[SPEAKER_07]: That's my reading of the Historical Commission.

993
01:34:22,495 --> 01:34:23,876
[SPEAKER_07]: So I appreciate that.

994
01:34:25,886 --> 01:34:35,636
[SPEAKER_07]: I don't think it's going to be a barrier here, but one of the things we did in Medford Square is we incentivized by historical buildings by giving them more height to save the building.

995
01:34:35,816 --> 01:34:40,280
[SPEAKER_07]: But if you look at what we're doing now, we're giving a lot of height before.

996
01:34:40,761 --> 01:34:47,728
[SPEAKER_07]: In other words, if we give three or four floors and there is other ways to get there, historical won't be important.

997
01:34:48,566 --> 01:34:57,054
[SPEAKER_07]: because they can do the green score, there's other ways to get to that, then the historical will be meaningless in those two historical buildings that I talked about, the two St.

998
01:34:57,074 --> 01:35:13,848
[SPEAKER_07]: Commons ones, because we've already given them so much height to begin with and then added a few floors on top of it that I feel like we might lose the carrot and stick approach that I think we successfully did in Medford Square to, I think, have a solid

999
01:35:14,489 --> 01:35:16,491
[SPEAKER_07]: preservation approach to those buildings?

1000
01:35:16,571 --> 01:35:24,819
[SPEAKER_07]: If not, there's no guarantees as everyone has discussed many times about saving really any historic building without some incredible efforts.

1001
01:35:25,460 --> 01:35:26,961
[SPEAKER_07]: Anyway, do you have any other final comments?

1002
01:35:27,001 --> 01:35:28,643
[SPEAKER_07]: I appreciate those excellent comments.

1003
01:35:31,243 --> 01:35:31,803
[SPEAKER_07]: Sounds like you're good.

1004
01:35:32,463 --> 01:35:33,144
[SPEAKER_03]: That's it for now.

1005
01:35:33,384 --> 01:35:33,704
[SPEAKER_03]: Thank you.

