1040
01:37:47,470 --> 01:37:49,172
[SPEAKER_24]: And that was mostly there.

1041
01:37:49,192 --> 01:37:52,855
[SPEAKER_24]: This is actually one parcel.

1042
01:37:52,915 --> 01:37:54,396
[SPEAKER_24]: It's staying as one parcel.

1043
01:37:54,416 --> 01:37:56,878
[SPEAKER_24]: They're not subdividing it into separate lots.

1044
01:37:57,799 --> 01:38:00,561
[SPEAKER_24]: So it's just multiple primary buildings on one lot.

1045
01:38:02,362 --> 01:38:04,883
[SPEAKER_24]: It's sort of different when you have one owner.

1046
01:38:05,283 --> 01:38:07,504
[SPEAKER_24]: Like it's kind of a mini campus in a way.

1047
01:38:07,524 --> 01:38:10,085
[SPEAKER_24]: Is that sort of what you're getting at?

1048
01:38:10,326 --> 01:38:15,267
[SPEAKER_22]: Yes, because I think this is a wonderful way to show how to use a big parcel.

1049
01:38:15,868 --> 01:38:28,553
[SPEAKER_22]: And with Elizabeth Grady abutting this on the other side of the tracks, this is a really good example of how it's granted that one building on the top is very close to North Street and not set back.

1050
01:38:29,213 --> 01:38:33,816
[SPEAKER_22]: which is, there's no step back or set back, I think, from this image.

1051
01:38:34,216 --> 01:38:38,339
[SPEAKER_22]: So I think that's a really good example of what we could be looking at on Boston Ave.

1052
01:38:39,880 --> 01:38:45,263
[SPEAKER_22]: So I'm hopeful that we can get creative when we're incentivizing who we want to see in these other parcels.

1053
01:38:46,123 --> 01:38:48,384
[SPEAKER_22]: But I do appreciate, Chairman Carr, what you suggested.

1054
01:38:48,404 --> 01:38:49,404
[SPEAKER_22]: I am in agreement.

1055
01:38:49,524 --> 01:39:03,007
[SPEAKER_22]: And even on the BA2 with the four-level, four-story condos and then the sphere, I think if there's another max height that's over there, those neighbors are going to be in shadows, potentially.

1056
01:39:03,367 --> 01:39:04,767
[SPEAKER_22]: So I do agree with that as well.

1057
01:39:06,788 --> 01:39:12,989
[SPEAKER_22]: It was interesting to hear about, and I know my colleague mentioned, the incentivizing of both underground parking.

1058
01:39:13,809 --> 01:39:17,510
[SPEAKER_22]: So I know that in other areas of the city, we want covered parking.

1059
01:39:18,130 --> 01:39:20,031
[SPEAKER_22]: So how do we work around that?

1060
01:39:20,071 --> 01:39:22,191
[SPEAKER_22]: And I don't know, obviously, you kind of spoke to that.

1061
01:39:22,691 --> 01:39:35,235
[SPEAKER_22]: But as an incentive, if we want covered parking, yet if it isn't feasible, and I know it's per site and per development, I just want to make sure that we have good, we have feasible incentives.

1062
01:39:36,934 --> 01:39:38,556
[SPEAKER_17]: Yes I'll answer that if I may.

1063
01:39:39,117 --> 01:39:54,035
[SPEAKER_17]: So the discussion at the meeting on Monday of the gentleman who spoke mentioned that underground parking in this area would be in particularly in the South Boston area I think would be South Boston area would be infeasible because of the high water table.

1064
01:39:54,055 --> 01:39:55,137
[SPEAKER_17]: It would be very expensive.

1065
01:39:55,677 --> 01:39:58,719
[SPEAKER_17]: Underground parking in general is very expensive.

1066
01:39:58,819 --> 01:40:02,241
[SPEAKER_17]: So the number that we had been using was $80,000 a space.

1067
01:40:02,682 --> 01:40:06,064
[SPEAKER_17]: He updated that to $90,000 to $100,000 a space.

1068
01:40:06,484 --> 01:40:11,227
[SPEAKER_17]: But you don't have to have underground parking in order to have covered parking.

1069
01:40:11,367 --> 01:40:18,912
[SPEAKER_17]: And so, for example, some of the site sections that Paola showed, there was one that showed parking at a lower level.

1070
01:40:19,412 --> 01:40:20,594
[SPEAKER_17]: with buildings in front.

1071
01:40:20,654 --> 01:40:24,660
[SPEAKER_17]: And so what you have there is you've created a parking podium.

1072
01:40:24,760 --> 01:40:26,682
[SPEAKER_17]: So that's actually above ground.

1073
01:40:27,183 --> 01:40:31,790
[SPEAKER_17]: You can have and actually the existing buildings in that area show that.

1074
01:40:32,333 --> 01:40:48,544
[SPEAKER_17]: You can have a liner building like a commercial along the street parking behind it and then residential above without having to actually go below ground and that's helped by the topography on some of the sites or it can just be how you've constructed the building.

1075
01:40:49,044 --> 01:40:54,168
[SPEAKER_17]: The existing housing in the Boston Avenue area the South Boston Avenue area.

1076
01:40:54,508 --> 01:40:58,250
[SPEAKER_17]: does have that parking on the first level with the building above.

1077
01:40:58,490 --> 01:41:05,714
[SPEAKER_17]: So that's a way that you can have that covered parking without being the additional expense of it being actually underground parking.

1078
01:41:06,615 --> 01:41:15,559
[SPEAKER_24]: I just want to add that we expect, so I mentioned that there was the Titan Gas property has had gotten approval for a project.

1079
01:41:16,000 --> 01:41:21,803
[SPEAKER_24]: So if you look really closely, actually, they are on a property that slants down.

1080
01:41:22,383 --> 01:41:30,270
[SPEAKER_24]: So at Boston Ave, their first floor would be up like, I think they had designed it to be up about three or four steps.

1081
01:41:30,871 --> 01:41:35,094
[SPEAKER_24]: And then their driveway goes next to their building and down underneath the building.

1082
01:41:35,555 --> 01:41:39,338
[SPEAKER_24]: And so if you're standing in the back, it looks like podium parking.

1083
01:41:39,718 --> 01:41:43,282
[SPEAKER_24]: If you're standing on Boston Ave, it looks like underground parking.

1084
01:41:43,822 --> 01:41:51,427
[SPEAKER_24]: And it is our expectation that the site that's right behind this one, we'll just keep calling it the Elizabeth Grady site.

1085
01:41:51,467 --> 01:41:57,870
[SPEAKER_24]: And just to be clear, I don't mean just that building, but all those parcels right there together, is also slanted like that.

1086
01:41:58,291 --> 01:42:05,475
[SPEAKER_24]: And we've looked at a couple of very tentative ideas over the last six years, and every one of them had something very similar.

1087
01:42:06,015 --> 01:42:13,318
[SPEAKER_24]: where at ground level, you would have your first floor of your building, but your cars would drive in and drive down.

1088
01:42:13,399 --> 01:42:24,904
[SPEAKER_24]: And you could do at least one level of parking that would be on Boston Ave underground, but at the back by the railroad tracks would be open and podium.

1089
01:42:24,964 --> 01:42:33,328
[SPEAKER_24]: So that has some digging into the ground, but it's not expensive the way you completely excavate a basement would be.

1090
01:42:33,888 --> 01:42:38,509
[SPEAKER_24]: So, we do think we would have some of that in some areas, particularly at those two sites.

1091
01:42:39,009 --> 01:42:48,911
[SPEAKER_22]: I appreciate that, because I want to make sure, and I know you all have done so much work and everybody here, that the incentives, we want people to come, we want to develop, so I just want to make sure that they're feasible, and they are.

1092
01:42:49,511 --> 01:42:55,792
[SPEAKER_22]: A quick question about, just because I have personal experience where I own my skincare salon, which is on this strip.

1093
01:42:56,832 --> 01:42:59,593
[SPEAKER_22]: So, I'm part of the section of BA1, and

1094
01:43:02,365 --> 01:43:06,969
[SPEAKER_22]: Although I do appreciate the zero setbacks, front, back.

1095
01:43:07,470 --> 01:43:10,132
[SPEAKER_22]: And I do understand my strip is nine units.

1096
01:43:11,233 --> 01:43:12,494
[SPEAKER_22]: There's ledge behind us.

1097
01:43:12,755 --> 01:43:14,476
[SPEAKER_22]: It's a huge retaining wall with ledge.

1098
01:43:15,017 --> 01:43:16,918
[SPEAKER_22]: So how would we work around that?

1099
01:43:17,139 --> 01:43:21,823
[SPEAKER_22]: And granted, I mean, if it's developed, it's developed as it should with housing above.

1100
01:43:22,804 --> 01:43:28,671
[SPEAKER_22]: But I just want to make sure that we are really staying true to the comprehensive plan with green score.

1101
01:43:29,011 --> 01:43:30,593
[SPEAKER_22]: And I appreciate the permeable surfaces.

1102
01:43:31,554 --> 01:43:34,317
[SPEAKER_22]: But that is, it's a tiny lot, but it's a long lot.

1103
01:43:34,998 --> 01:43:36,160
[SPEAKER_22]: So how do we work with that?

1104
01:43:40,948 --> 01:43:47,512
[SPEAKER_17]: Just to clarify, the issue is that the rear of the lot has ledge on it.

1105
01:43:47,892 --> 01:43:55,156
[SPEAKER_17]: So right now, the front setback is proposed to be a zero front setback, which would actually accommodate you because it's not pushing you backwards.

1106
01:43:55,616 --> 01:44:02,600
[SPEAKER_17]: The 20-foot setback comes in if you're wanting to put a plaza or something in front of it, but it's not required.

1107
01:44:03,060 --> 01:44:07,026
[SPEAKER_17]: So you would be what you, I believe you are now, is along the lot line.

1108
01:44:07,627 --> 01:44:09,770
[SPEAKER_17]: That would be no change, so.

1109
01:44:10,731 --> 01:44:17,441
[SPEAKER_17]: You do bring up an interesting point, and I know we probably say it once at every meeting, but I do want to confirm, I think we touched

1110
01:44:17,942 --> 01:44:26,607
[SPEAKER_17]: Collectively, we touched on it earlier, but when zoning changes, that doesn't mean that existing properties have to change to match the new zoning.

1111
01:44:26,627 --> 01:44:35,612
[SPEAKER_17]: So those properties would stay as is until somebody came along to develop, but in that case, the front setback is actually your friend because it's not pushing you into that ledge.

1112
01:44:36,552 --> 01:44:43,436
[SPEAKER_17]: There are usually, I mean, there are the opportunity if somebody came in and wanted to do something different and they couldn't meet

1113
01:44:45,178 --> 01:44:51,164
[SPEAKER_17]: Some of the other things there is of course the ZBA process if they're going to be requesting waivers on that.

1114
01:44:51,445 --> 01:45:01,456
[SPEAKER_17]: There are also some other waivers that are built into the proposed zoning to allow the CD board flexibility to address some of these existing conditions that might be tricky.

1115
01:45:02,437 --> 01:45:16,405
[SPEAKER_17]: In general, a combination of a waiver that's allowed by the CD board, and we've talked about some of them already, or an actual requirement from, or an actual application to the ZBA should cover many situations.

1116
01:45:17,926 --> 01:45:24,690
[SPEAKER_17]: Now the palette is reminding me that it's not just the zero setback, but it's a sidewalk setback as well.

1117
01:45:25,170 --> 01:45:31,376
[SPEAKER_17]: And you do actually have a waiver as a CD board for new construction.

1118
01:45:31,416 --> 01:45:43,368
[SPEAKER_17]: So if your building were to be torn down and somebody was proposing new construction, then we have the requirement that it has to be set back from the lot line at a distance sufficient to create the 12 foot setback.

1119
01:45:46,030 --> 01:45:51,514
[SPEAKER_17]: So if the existing sidewalk is five feet, it would have to be set back seven feet.

1120
01:45:51,854 --> 01:45:53,756
[SPEAKER_17]: You have the issue with the ledge, as you pointed out.

1121
01:45:54,116 --> 01:45:58,579
[SPEAKER_17]: So there's a waiver in here because we did recognize that there was some topographical challenges.

1122
01:45:58,719 --> 01:46:08,347
[SPEAKER_17]: If that's not, if that can't happen, then the setback requirement, the CD board has the ability to bring that down to an eight foot setback.

1123
01:46:09,408 --> 01:46:19,338
[SPEAKER_17]: So therefore, if the public sidewalk is already five feet, you would only have to add three feet in order to meet that requirement.

1124
01:46:19,598 --> 01:46:26,505
[SPEAKER_17]: So we could consider whether or not we need to add additional flexibility given the presence of ledge.

1125
01:46:26,545 --> 01:46:31,950
[SPEAKER_17]: And that's certainly something that we can talk about as part of the policy decisions that you all are making today.

1126
01:46:32,611 --> 01:46:32,911
[SPEAKER_22]: Perfect.

1127
01:46:33,031 --> 01:46:33,611
[SPEAKER_22]: Thank you so much.

1128
01:46:33,651 --> 01:46:38,473
[SPEAKER_22]: And I think using my the building where I'm at is a great example because it's such a tiny lot.

1129
01:46:38,813 --> 01:46:46,516
[SPEAKER_22]: But I think it just shows also there are other areas on this corridor that could use a setback and would be appropriate.

1130
01:46:46,796 --> 01:46:48,737
[SPEAKER_22]: So I do want to be really mindful of that.

1131
01:46:49,137 --> 01:47:05,643
[SPEAKER_22]: Yes, that little strip, totally, that makes sense, but I think we do really need to look at the other ones, because I think a setback is appropriate, and stepbacks too, because that was something that I learned in the square of how wonderful that is to still grab the units that we really want for housing, but not make people in shadows.

1132
01:47:06,944 --> 01:47:20,634
[SPEAKER_17]: Absolutely, and we do have a step back, so just for terminology for people at home, step back is the upper level floors stepping back from the facade, from the front facade.

1133
01:47:21,375 --> 01:47:35,626
[SPEAKER_17]: We also have those requirements, same as we talked about in Medford Square, about if you're next, if the building is next to a residential district, it does have to meet certain requirements for step backs on those upper stories, that's that 45 degree plane that we talked about.

1134
01:47:35,986 --> 01:47:37,827
[SPEAKER_17]: So, those have all been retained in this.

1135
01:47:37,887 --> 01:47:40,489
[SPEAKER_17]: I think we learned those lessons during the Medford Square.

1136
01:47:40,509 --> 01:47:41,250
[SPEAKER_17]: So, thank you for that.

1137
01:47:41,270 --> 01:47:41,670
[SPEAKER_22]: So, thank you.

1138
01:47:41,970 --> 01:47:44,872
[SPEAKER_22]: And I have just one more, and I would love to pass the mic.

1139
01:47:45,393 --> 01:47:51,297
[SPEAKER_22]: We did get a lot of public comment, and I know a lot of us didn't get it this afternoon, which it's to no fault of anyone's.

1140
01:47:51,817 --> 01:47:55,179
[SPEAKER_22]: So, we all are looking at public comment and listening to public comment.

1141
01:47:55,480 --> 01:47:59,923
[SPEAKER_22]: But one that I did see that was actually fascinating was about data centers.

1142
01:48:00,563 --> 01:48:02,785
[SPEAKER_22]: And that's not something that we had talked about.

1143
01:48:03,585 --> 01:48:06,528
[SPEAKER_22]: And it's an interesting thing that is going on.

1144
01:48:06,968 --> 01:48:12,232
[SPEAKER_22]: So I didn't know if you had any experience with data centers or zoning around data centers.

1145
01:48:12,393 --> 01:48:14,955
[SPEAKER_22]: But I do think it was brought publicly.

1146
01:48:15,395 --> 01:48:18,557
[SPEAKER_22]: So I would just like to hear what you all have experienced with that.

1147
01:48:19,478 --> 01:48:22,441
[SPEAKER_17]: So we have not yet done zoning for data centers.

1148
01:48:22,481 --> 01:48:25,043
[SPEAKER_17]: It's actually zoning for data centers is relatively new.

1149
01:48:25,964 --> 01:48:32,130
[SPEAKER_17]: One of our former clients actually is one of the first towns to bring one forward.

1150
01:48:32,190 --> 01:48:33,471
[SPEAKER_17]: So is that fast.

1151
01:48:33,531 --> 01:48:35,914
[SPEAKER_17]: I can't wait to get a chance to read it and look at it.

1152
01:48:38,175 --> 01:48:43,258
[SPEAKER_17]: So, data centers are currently not allowed at the level that we all think of as data centers.

1153
01:48:43,318 --> 01:48:53,243
[SPEAKER_17]: Obviously, an individual building can have its wiring closet and all that, but those single-use data centers are not currently in your table of uses.

1154
01:48:53,703 --> 01:48:56,125
[SPEAKER_17]: They're also very large.

1155
01:48:57,485 --> 01:49:09,809
[SPEAKER_17]: And so I'd have to look and see what the average size is, but just my memory of some of the size of buildings I've seen and the parcels you have available to you here, I'm not sure one would fit.

1156
01:49:10,189 --> 01:49:14,991
[SPEAKER_17]: But we can take another look and actually it gives me an excuse to delve into the newest.

1157
01:49:15,011 --> 01:49:20,213
[SPEAKER_22]: Thank you for looking at that, but I think it would be important that saying how large and huge and

1158
01:49:20,773 --> 01:49:25,040
[SPEAKER_22]: potentially you know energy water whatever is used that we don't.

1159
01:49:25,420 --> 01:49:26,883
[SPEAKER_17]: So we can at the moment.

1160
01:49:27,003 --> 01:49:30,889
[SPEAKER_17]: So you have zoning that if it's not in your table of uses it can't be done.

1161
01:49:30,989 --> 01:49:34,875
[SPEAKER_17]: It's not currently in your table of uses so it is therefore not currently allowed.

1162
01:49:35,035 --> 01:49:35,496
[SPEAKER_17]: Excellent.

1163
01:49:35,636 --> 01:49:36,017
[SPEAKER_17]: Thank you.

1164
01:49:37,912 --> 01:49:38,432
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you, Paige.

1165
01:49:39,233 --> 01:49:39,994
[SPEAKER_07]: Just a couple of comments.

1166
01:49:41,035 --> 01:49:41,615
[SPEAKER_07]: Excellent comments.

1167
01:49:41,635 --> 01:49:41,995
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you.

1168
01:49:42,756 --> 01:49:56,768
[SPEAKER_07]: The one thing I'm pretty sure of, as much as I agree with you about the Walkling Court as a great zoning and massing and step up away from the neighborhood, it's a much bigger parcel.

1169
01:49:56,968 --> 01:50:01,712
[SPEAKER_07]: And I am quite confident, knowing my developer clients, because I think like them for the last 20 years,

1170
01:50:02,712 --> 01:50:08,317
[SPEAKER_07]: They're going to put one building on the Elizabeth Grady site that will cover the almost as big a building as they can fit on that site.

1171
01:50:08,977 --> 01:50:13,241
[SPEAKER_07]: And they'll put parking and retail below and as many floors as we allow them to put above.

1172
01:50:13,841 --> 01:50:19,186
[SPEAKER_07]: I can almost guarantee any developer would take that approach because that's what developers do.

1173
01:50:19,406 --> 01:50:22,649
[SPEAKER_07]: You know, they don't, if you allow them seven, they're going to take seven.

1174
01:50:22,669 --> 01:50:23,549
[SPEAKER_07]: They're not going to take five.

1175
01:50:24,830 --> 01:50:25,431
[SPEAKER_07]: And that's okay.

1176
01:50:25,571 --> 01:50:26,612
[SPEAKER_07]: That's why we're doing this.

1177
01:50:26,792 --> 01:50:30,475
[SPEAKER_07]: We, you know, and it, you know, it's, the use is something we're debating.

1178
01:50:30,515 --> 01:50:31,496
[SPEAKER_07]: I think it's a healthy debate.

1179
01:50:32,796 --> 01:50:49,802
[SPEAKER_07]: But it will be, I think that what that requires us to do is assume that that building is tallest along the railroad track and finds a way to gently step down and then maybe with the 45 degrees on both streets to allow that morning sun, because it's not south, but it's east.

1180
01:50:50,768 --> 01:50:51,909
[SPEAKER_07]: and a little bit southeast.

1181
01:50:52,769 --> 01:50:55,772
[SPEAKER_07]: We don't want to cut off that light to the neighbors on Boston Ave.

1182
01:50:55,792 --> 01:51:04,158
[SPEAKER_07]: I think there's a way we can do that intelligently with any use, whether it's multifamily, even labs, which has been proposed, as Alicia said.

1183
01:51:04,758 --> 01:51:06,339
[SPEAKER_07]: So I think there's a way forward here.

1184
01:51:06,359 --> 01:51:10,462
[SPEAKER_07]: That's a lot of development, but still being sensitive.

1185
01:51:11,923 --> 01:51:14,005
[SPEAKER_07]: OK, Sean Began, you're next.

1186
01:51:16,887 --> 01:51:17,007
[SPEAKER_20]: Four.

1187
01:51:21,181 --> 01:51:21,521
[SPEAKER_05]: Go ahead, John.

1188
01:51:21,621 --> 01:51:23,082
[SPEAKER_05]: Thank you, Chairman Carr.

1189
01:51:23,623 --> 01:51:29,966
[SPEAKER_05]: Again, very, very thoughtful comments from all the board members tonight, and I think that really is the key.

1190
01:51:30,067 --> 01:51:35,930
[SPEAKER_05]: That was the key on Medford Square, and I think it's the key here to take our time and be thoughtful about this approach.

1191
01:51:37,491 --> 01:51:42,534
[SPEAKER_05]: I'm going to reiterate a couple points where I agree with what speakers have already said.

1192
01:51:43,255 --> 01:51:48,398
[SPEAKER_05]: One is the concept of adding a use for the privately owned student housing

1193
01:51:49,264 --> 01:51:53,866
[SPEAKER_05]: And when I say privately owned, I mean owned by other than an educational institution.

1194
01:51:55,327 --> 01:51:56,327
[SPEAKER_05]: I think that can work.

1195
01:51:56,407 --> 01:51:59,069
[SPEAKER_05]: I think that can be a nice benefit to the city.

1196
01:51:59,989 --> 01:52:05,812
[SPEAKER_05]: I think we have to be careful about the definition in terms of the size.

1197
01:52:06,052 --> 01:52:07,033
[SPEAKER_05]: I don't want to

1198
01:52:08,212 --> 01:52:15,777
[SPEAKER_05]: pass a privately owned student housing use that then allows a row of private fraternities.

1199
01:52:15,837 --> 01:52:20,200
[SPEAKER_05]: I wanted something that is going to be maybe a 200 person minimum.

1200
01:52:20,620 --> 01:52:27,505
[SPEAKER_05]: Something large enough that only developers that can really professionally manage

1201
01:52:28,353 --> 01:52:30,654
[SPEAKER_05]: a building are going to be involved.

1202
01:52:31,374 --> 01:52:39,938
[SPEAKER_05]: I think it's something that probably we would want to put some sort of annual licensing or permitting factor in as well such that there's review.

1203
01:52:41,479 --> 01:52:42,619
[SPEAKER_05]: But I think that can be done.

1204
01:52:42,639 --> 01:52:46,581
[SPEAKER_05]: I think it is a good idea and I would encourage adding that as a use.

1205
01:52:50,223 --> 01:52:59,790
[SPEAKER_05]: Chairman Carr on his proposal to eliminate the residential houses that he identified on Boston Ave, on both sides of Boston Ave in that location.

1206
01:53:01,371 --> 01:53:13,159
[SPEAKER_05]: And then in doing so, I would also propose that we eliminate from the use table the single family, two family, and three family dwellings from the BA1.

1207
01:53:15,320 --> 01:53:18,582
[SPEAKER_05]: I think what we're trying to do is build a commercial corridor here.

1208
01:53:21,207 --> 01:53:35,072
[SPEAKER_05]: when we start to put in residential uses or start to rezone residences, and I know these houses are in an apartment one zone, they're not necessarily in a residential zone, but they are residences.

1209
01:53:35,933 --> 01:53:44,116
[SPEAKER_05]: I think we're getting ahead of ourselves because I think one of the mandates of the agreement with the city council and the mayor is that residential would be done at the end.

1210
01:53:44,456 --> 01:53:49,718
[SPEAKER_05]: And I think if we have residential, small residential uses allowed here,

1211
01:53:50,578 --> 01:53:57,180
[SPEAKER_05]: We run the risk of first getting development that we don't really want here and isn't really the point.

1212
01:53:57,800 --> 01:54:12,263
[SPEAKER_05]: But secondly, in a way we're setting some precedent in terms of dimensional lot sizes for residential uses that might come back to bite us when we actually do residential zoning next year sometime.

1213
01:54:12,943 --> 01:54:19,225
[SPEAKER_05]: So that's what I have to say about the residential portion of Boston Ave.

1214
01:54:22,566 --> 01:54:27,310
[SPEAKER_05]: In terms of the heights, I'm comfortable with the BA1 as it is now.

1215
01:54:27,330 --> 01:54:28,872
[SPEAKER_05]: I wouldn't want to go higher.

1216
01:54:30,713 --> 01:54:36,379
[SPEAKER_05]: I think Chairman Carr is right on the money with the BA2 in terms of where that height should probably be.

1217
01:54:37,059 --> 01:54:45,687
[SPEAKER_05]: And then with the BA3, where those lots are so large and there's so much room off the street, perhaps we could have a height

1218
01:54:45,999 --> 01:54:55,885
[SPEAKER_05]: that varied as you got further back off the street so that when you're back at the tracks, as Chairman Carr said, perhaps you're higher than what's allowed right out on Boston Ave.

1219
01:54:55,905 --> 01:54:58,567
[SPEAKER_05]: So I think that would be worth talking about.

1220
01:55:01,669 --> 01:55:13,956
[SPEAKER_05]: And let's see, one other, oh, just one other ticky-tack thing that I always harp on is that right now we have a use, marijuana use as allowed by the ZBA and

1221
01:55:16,060 --> 01:55:19,822
[SPEAKER_05]: It's not allowed in the marijuana ordinance that we have in the city.

1222
01:55:19,882 --> 01:55:32,408
[SPEAKER_05]: So before we start putting it into our zoning, I think the correct thing to do is change the marijuana ordinance, say where you want to have marijuana retail and

1223
01:55:33,168 --> 01:55:35,690
[SPEAKER_05]: I have no opinion as to whether it should be on Boston Ave or not.

1224
01:55:35,710 --> 01:55:36,471
[SPEAKER_05]: I don't really care.

1225
01:55:37,291 --> 01:55:46,338
[SPEAKER_05]: For me, it's more a procedural thing of we can't say the ZBA can approve it here when the marijuana ordinance specifically says it can't be approved here.

1226
01:55:46,938 --> 01:55:59,408
[SPEAKER_05]: So I would say let's take that off or just maybe put a note or an asterisk that says refers them to the marijuana ordinance and then put in that ordinance all the areas where you want to allow marijuana retail.

1227
01:56:00,468 --> 01:56:02,470
[SPEAKER_05]: So that's all I have for right now.

1228
01:56:05,255 --> 01:56:05,735
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you, Sean.

1229
01:56:07,675 --> 01:56:09,356
[SPEAKER_07]: John Anderson, let me unmute you.

1230
01:56:12,716 --> 01:56:13,116
[SPEAKER_06]: Thank you.

1231
01:56:13,136 --> 01:56:16,537
[SPEAKER_06]: I don't know where to start.

1232
01:56:16,557 --> 01:56:22,638
[SPEAKER_06]: A lot of people have covered a lot of points already, and I really appreciate that.

1233
01:56:25,619 --> 01:56:27,579
[SPEAKER_06]: I'm just going to go in random order.

1234
01:56:28,619 --> 01:56:31,140
[SPEAKER_06]: One of the things that I don't really understand

1235
01:56:32,134 --> 01:56:36,077
[SPEAKER_06]: is the role of the Community Development Board versus zoning.

1236
01:56:36,557 --> 01:56:48,544
[SPEAKER_06]: This has come up in a couple of site plan reviews where the applicant has taken the position that, well, the zoning says that what I want to do is okay, so you can't tell me to do something different.

1237
01:56:49,505 --> 01:56:57,830
[SPEAKER_06]: Now, it never really came to blows or court cases because they were looking for a quick approval, so they relented.

1238
01:56:58,784 --> 01:57:01,045
[SPEAKER_06]: and would go along with our requests.

1239
01:57:01,505 --> 01:57:19,214
[SPEAKER_06]: But my question is, if push came to shove, can the Community Development Board, given the design standards that we have, say, okay, the zoning says you can put up a six-story building, but in this particular situation, that would be unfair to the neighbors, so you can't?

1240
01:57:21,095 --> 01:57:22,796
[SPEAKER_06]: I just don't know the answer to that question.

1241
01:57:22,836 --> 01:57:26,438
[SPEAKER_06]: I know the attorneys for some of our applicants have

1242
01:57:27,037 --> 01:57:28,698
[SPEAKER_06]: have a particular viewpoint on that.

1243
01:57:30,940 --> 01:57:34,242
[SPEAKER_07]: I obviously think that's a question for Alicia and the staff.

1244
01:57:34,403 --> 01:57:35,684
[SPEAKER_07]: I don't think we should tackle that here.

1245
01:57:35,704 --> 01:57:36,624
[SPEAKER_07]: You're raising it as an issue.

1246
01:57:36,644 --> 01:57:37,585
[SPEAKER_07]: I think it's a good issue.

1247
01:57:37,605 --> 01:57:39,446
[SPEAKER_07]: I don't think we want to.

1248
01:57:39,847 --> 01:57:40,127
[SPEAKER_06]: I know.

1249
01:57:40,887 --> 01:57:41,868
[SPEAKER_06]: I don't want to debate it.

1250
01:57:42,369 --> 01:57:44,750
[SPEAKER_06]: I'm just saying, though, it gives us an out.

1251
01:57:46,271 --> 01:57:49,354
[SPEAKER_06]: If we trust the Community Development Board, which I certainly do,

1252
01:57:52,018 --> 01:57:58,826
[SPEAKER_06]: Then if something slips through the zoning and it's subject to site point review, there's a backstop there.

1253
01:57:58,906 --> 01:58:00,148
[SPEAKER_06]: That's the only point I'm making.

1254
01:58:03,091 --> 01:58:08,077
[SPEAKER_06]: I'm concerned that we've never tackled the definition of high frequent transit.

1255
01:58:09,397 --> 01:58:12,621
[SPEAKER_24]: Before you go on, could I just sort of address something?

1256
01:58:13,942 --> 01:58:25,115
[SPEAKER_24]: If something is allowed under the zoning, it's a yes, and the height is allowed, then the CD board cannot just say, no, we don't want to do it.

1257
01:58:25,255 --> 01:58:27,377
[SPEAKER_24]: We don't want to allow it under site plan review.

1258
01:58:28,218 --> 01:58:29,379
[SPEAKER_24]: Like it's allowed.

1259
01:58:29,399 --> 01:58:30,920
[SPEAKER_24]: They have a right to do it.

1260
01:58:31,581 --> 01:58:35,984
[SPEAKER_24]: If it's a special permit that's where you have right.

1261
01:58:36,024 --> 01:58:38,266
[SPEAKER_24]: So if the use is CDB then it's allowed.

1262
01:58:38,566 --> 01:58:47,694
[SPEAKER_24]: But if we say that a seven story building is allowed there and then they but it has to go through site plan review because it's a large building.

1263
01:58:48,254 --> 01:58:51,517
[SPEAKER_24]: The CD board can't just say no we don't want it.

1264
01:58:53,519 --> 01:58:53,879
[SPEAKER_24]: You want to.

1265
01:58:54,059 --> 01:58:55,720
[SPEAKER_24]: Danielle's gonna be more nuanced I think.

1266
01:59:00,352 --> 01:59:03,934
[SPEAKER_25]: So I don't exactly agree with that.

1267
01:59:04,514 --> 01:59:20,583
[SPEAKER_25]: Site plan review, you can condition things and say that it can be lower, but if that equates to making it like uneconomic or not developable, then they can say that these conditions basically equate to a no and a denial and you can't deny the buy right use.

1268
01:59:21,163 --> 01:59:37,232
[SPEAKER_25]: But I think it's totally within the purview of a site plan review authority to say, you know, to mitigate the various criteria and standards that say this,

1269
01:59:38,251 --> 01:59:50,014
[SPEAKER_25]: You know, eight stories on the east side of the building would have a detrimental effect and would shadow and all of this, and should be stepped back, or the footprint should be changed.

1270
01:59:51,254 --> 01:59:59,956
[SPEAKER_25]: It's not just a yes, you have this envelope you can build to, and if you say no to that, someone's dragging you to court.

1271
02:00:00,576 --> 02:00:01,397
[SPEAKER_25]: I don't agree with that.

1272
02:00:03,097 --> 02:00:05,237
[SPEAKER_25]: But they have to be defensible reasons.

1273
02:00:08,945 --> 02:00:16,732
[SPEAKER_25]: If they appeal it to land court, which they're entitled to do, it depends what a judge would say.

1274
02:00:16,772 --> 02:00:27,542
[SPEAKER_25]: I also saw that, I'm not sure where it's going, but the state legislature was looking at adding site plan review.

1275
02:00:28,402 --> 02:00:33,844
[SPEAKER_25]: to Chapter 48, which is the Zoning Enabling Act that governs what we can put in our zoning.

1276
02:00:34,145 --> 02:00:36,506
[SPEAKER_25]: Cuz right now, 48 doesn't have site plan review.

1277
02:00:36,546 --> 02:00:38,346
[SPEAKER_25]: It's really a creature of local government.

1278
02:00:39,907 --> 02:00:40,867
[SPEAKER_25]: So this could all change.

1279
02:00:41,568 --> 02:00:41,668
[SPEAKER_25]: Yeah.

1280
02:00:43,783 --> 02:00:47,767
[SPEAKER_06]: Well, that certainly backs up your position, Doug, that this needs further discussion.

1281
02:00:52,951 --> 02:01:04,661
[SPEAKER_06]: The issue of noise with certain uses came up, and perhaps this is something we could toss to the city council to review their noise ordinance if there is one.

1282
02:01:06,803 --> 02:01:07,264
[SPEAKER_06]: Is there one?

1283
02:01:08,703 --> 02:01:09,063
[SPEAKER_06]: Oh good.

1284
02:01:09,083 --> 02:01:10,404
[SPEAKER_20]: The city has a noise ordinance.

1285
02:01:10,504 --> 02:01:12,846
[SPEAKER_20]: It's one of the oldest ordinances the city has.

1286
02:01:12,986 --> 02:01:13,507
[SPEAKER_06]: That's great.

1287
02:01:13,967 --> 02:01:18,991
[SPEAKER_06]: But these sorts of issues should you know the noise or should be able to deal with situations like that.

1288
02:01:22,934 --> 02:01:38,405
[SPEAKER_06]: I'm concerned that the definition of high frequency transit is still floating around out there and it came up in the context of site plan review of a building on Salem Street and there was some real ambiguity there.

1289
02:01:39,816 --> 02:01:43,479
[SPEAKER_06]: And I don't think it's just the ambiguity.

1290
02:01:44,040 --> 02:01:46,602
[SPEAKER_06]: I think the concept needs to be looked at more carefully.

1291
02:01:47,523 --> 02:02:00,654
[SPEAKER_06]: I can say just from personal experience, my house has pretty good transit if you want to commute to Boston every morning or maybe even Cambridge.

1292
02:02:00,675 --> 02:02:06,700
[SPEAKER_06]: And I unfortunately was not able to use it except for a couple of years when I had a job in Kendall Square.

1293
02:02:07,820 --> 02:02:14,503
[SPEAKER_06]: But even when I was working in Kendall Square and had a T-pass, I think I used it once other than to go to work.

1294
02:02:15,424 --> 02:02:24,769
[SPEAKER_06]: Just because the service didn't accommodate, you know, going to the museum, coming home within an hour or two of when I wanted to.

1295
02:02:24,829 --> 02:02:26,350
[SPEAKER_06]: It just didn't work.

1296
02:02:27,850 --> 02:02:32,853
[SPEAKER_06]: So there's kind of two kinds of, you know, there's high frequency to get to work and there's high frequency for

1297
02:02:34,122 --> 02:02:41,645
[SPEAKER_06]: pleasure outings and one means you don't need a car and the other means you do need a car or you need to have a big Uber bill.

1298
02:02:45,786 --> 02:02:57,170
[SPEAKER_06]: I think the, getting back to parking again, there's some material in here that talks about shared parking and how that can reduce the parking requirements.

1299
02:02:58,506 --> 02:03:04,148
[SPEAKER_06]: I found that extremely confusing and if some more examples worked out, would be very helpful.

1300
02:03:11,011 --> 02:03:14,752
[SPEAKER_06]: Another issue that came up discussing green features.

1301
02:03:16,513 --> 02:03:20,834
[SPEAKER_06]: A developer gets points, for example, not cutting down a nice big tree.

1302
02:03:22,035 --> 02:03:24,656
[SPEAKER_06]: What happens if a year or two later,

1303
02:03:26,147 --> 02:03:31,808
[SPEAKER_06]: the developer sells the building to someone else who gets tired of paying to have the leaves raked and cuts it down.

1304
02:03:33,108 --> 02:03:36,949
[SPEAKER_06]: They got an extra story for leaving the tree and now what?

1305
02:03:42,150 --> 02:03:47,291
[SPEAKER_06]: I'm at a loss as to how one might deal with that with zoning.

1306
02:03:49,132 --> 02:03:52,392
[SPEAKER_06]: Even if you attach stuff like that to the deed, who would enforce it?

1307
02:03:58,611 --> 02:04:08,978
[SPEAKER_06]: Am I correct in assuming that almost all development is going to take advantage of one or more of the incentive bonuses to get to the height they want?

1308
02:04:09,639 --> 02:04:19,265
[SPEAKER_07]: I don't think there's a guarantee, but the way it's structured by Emily and what we've seen, I think it's likely they'll go for it because the values are so big, getting an extra floor or two.

1309
02:04:20,086 --> 02:04:22,687
[SPEAKER_07]: They'd be crazy not to, in my opinion, as developers.

1310
02:04:23,168 --> 02:04:24,228
[SPEAKER_07]: That's my personal opinion.

1311
02:04:24,248 --> 02:04:26,190
[SPEAKER_07]: I don't know, Emily, if you have any...

1312
02:04:28,446 --> 02:04:29,527
[SPEAKER_07]: Additional thoughts on that?

1313
02:04:31,189 --> 02:04:35,074
[SPEAKER_17]: I'm sorry, official thoughts on whether or not a developer would take the incentive?

1314
02:04:35,094 --> 02:04:45,907
[SPEAKER_07]: On the incentive, the likelihood that it will be engaged by developers, that they'll get those extra stories by going for the extra, you know, the things that, in some cases, the historic and the green.

1315
02:04:47,689 --> 02:04:57,334
[SPEAKER_17]: So the question, as I understand it, is whether or not a developer would be more likely to take advantage of the incentives.

1316
02:04:57,814 --> 02:05:09,760
[SPEAKER_17]: We structured it as a menu, and actually this goes back quite a ways in Medford zoning because we first talked about it with the MBTA Communities Act in terms of structuring incentives.

1317
02:05:10,360 --> 02:05:14,163
[SPEAKER_17]: The problem with development is it's very dependent on market cycles.

1318
02:05:14,403 --> 02:05:27,193
[SPEAKER_17]: And the point of having a menu structure is to allow a developer to make choices based on which market cycle they're in as to which types of incentives they could go after.

1319
02:05:28,814 --> 02:05:33,556
[SPEAKER_17]: And although they are stackable to a certain extent, they are limited by the height.

1320
02:05:33,997 --> 02:05:48,845
[SPEAKER_17]: One of the reasons for having the, the base heights in this district be lower and the incentive heights be higher is to encourage them to take the incentives because those incentives provide public benefit.

1321
02:05:48,885 --> 02:05:52,727
[SPEAKER_17]: That's why you're doing it, right, is you're, you're, you're giving the additional density.

1322
02:05:53,367 --> 02:05:55,108
[SPEAKER_17]: in order to have that public benefit.

1323
02:05:56,489 --> 02:06:02,293
[SPEAKER_17]: It would be interesting because the incentive is, of course, dependent on the size of the floor.

1324
02:06:02,813 --> 02:06:19,845
[SPEAKER_17]: So in a smaller building, say a building that has a 2,000, 3,000 square foot footprint, adding a single floor of height for some of those incentives, say for the affordable housing ones,

1325
02:06:20,565 --> 02:06:22,566
[SPEAKER_17]: They might not actually get that much out of it.

1326
02:06:23,226 --> 02:06:31,648
[SPEAKER_17]: You're more likely to get a developer taking advantage of it if they are dealing with a larger site and the market works well with what they're doing.

1327
02:06:31,748 --> 02:06:35,449
[SPEAKER_17]: So that's why the structure is set up the way it is.

1328
02:06:36,169 --> 02:06:47,152
[SPEAKER_17]: Certainly we just brought forward, as we did with the development standards, as we did with the shared parking, we just brought forward what was in Medford Square as that opening point for your discussion.

1329
02:06:47,192 --> 02:06:48,472
[SPEAKER_17]: You're already familiar with it.

1330
02:06:49,012 --> 02:06:58,199
[SPEAKER_17]: It made sense, I think Chairman Carr made the point that there aren't as many historic buildings in the area that might take advantage of the historic incentives.

1331
02:06:58,219 --> 02:07:03,082
[SPEAKER_17]: It becomes up to you whether or not you want to leave those in or take those out.

1332
02:07:04,583 --> 02:07:13,410
[SPEAKER_17]: But I don't know that it's an automatic that a developer would go to the maximum height based on the incentives because it's not just the incentives that

1333
02:07:14,190 --> 02:07:22,677
[SPEAKER_17]: There are other components of the dimensional standards and requirements that might reduce the height such that they could not take advantage of the incentives.

1334
02:07:24,539 --> 02:07:24,959
[SPEAKER_06]: Go ahead, John.

1335
02:07:25,219 --> 02:07:42,133
[SPEAKER_06]: Well, that raises the question of instead of rewarding developers for taking one of the incentives, require them to pick from this list of things they can do that add value to the neighborhood.

1336
02:07:43,849 --> 02:07:48,550
[SPEAKER_06]: In other words, require them to pick some options.

1337
02:07:50,000 --> 02:08:13,847
[SPEAKER_17]: So we do have to be careful there, because we may get into a situation that's called a regulatory taking, where we are creating such a disparity in the value by requiring them to do something that they're losing economic value, and therefore, A, they could just simply walk away from it, and then the community gets nothing.

1338
02:08:15,587 --> 02:08:25,370
[SPEAKER_17]: I tend to prefer the carrots to the sticks when writing zoning, so I'm more likely to recommend that my clients consider incentives.

1339
02:08:25,930 --> 02:08:31,531
[SPEAKER_17]: I have heard arguments to the contrary, that incentives should not be considered.

1340
02:08:31,811 --> 02:08:43,974
[SPEAKER_17]: And to your point, maybe it's just a requirement, but I would be very careful that you would have to structure those requirements so as not to cause either

1341
02:08:44,494 --> 02:08:50,959
[SPEAKER_17]: the economic value to be substantially diminished or to run the risk that the development doesn't happen at all.

1342
02:08:51,139 --> 02:08:56,083
[SPEAKER_17]: So not saying no, just saying that there's these additional considerations.

1343
02:08:56,404 --> 02:09:10,815
[SPEAKER_06]: Because I do know that many cities have tree ordinances, which require you when you build something or tear something down, you have to put in a certain number of trees, which also could affect the economic value of the development.

1344
02:09:11,157 --> 02:09:17,440
[SPEAKER_07]: Well, we've seen that, John, ourselves, right, in our own projects on Salem Street and Main Street just in the last three months, right?

1345
02:09:17,460 --> 02:09:17,680
[SPEAKER_07]: Yeah.

1346
02:09:17,860 --> 02:09:19,521
[SPEAKER_07]: We've seen that in action, actually.

1347
02:09:19,541 --> 02:09:20,861
[SPEAKER_07]: Great.

1348
02:09:23,462 --> 02:09:27,304
[SPEAKER_03]: Those are legislative not zoning, though, typically, is my understanding.

1349
02:09:30,007 --> 02:09:30,487
[SPEAKER_06]: Who said that?

1350
02:09:30,567 --> 02:09:31,268
[SPEAKER_07]: That's Ari.

1351
02:09:31,728 --> 02:09:34,410
[SPEAKER_07]: That's the ghost of Ari online.

1352
02:09:35,811 --> 02:09:36,252
[SPEAKER_06]: Sorry.

1353
02:09:36,272 --> 02:09:36,732
[SPEAKER_06]: Hi.

1354
02:09:37,573 --> 02:09:38,153
[SPEAKER_06]: That's OK.

1355
02:09:38,173 --> 02:09:39,194
[SPEAKER_06]: The disembodied voice.

1356
02:09:39,214 --> 02:09:40,195
[SPEAKER_07]: She's obviously unmuted.

1357
02:09:48,005 --> 02:10:00,851
[SPEAKER_17]: If I may, just to add to that, the green score, which you all have, you, the city, not necessarily you all personally, but the green score, which has already been adopted by the city, does have those requirements.

1358
02:10:00,991 --> 02:10:05,933
[SPEAKER_17]: The developer must meet the green score requirements if they hit the thresholds.

1359
02:10:07,073 --> 02:10:10,855
[SPEAKER_17]: And we actually went through those in fair depth on Monday.

1360
02:10:10,955 --> 02:10:13,956
[SPEAKER_17]: I have to give all credit to the patience of the people there.

1361
02:10:14,996 --> 02:10:17,497
[SPEAKER_17]: of exactly what would be required for the green score.

1362
02:10:17,517 --> 02:10:19,458
[SPEAKER_17]: That is existing and that is required.

1363
02:10:21,639 --> 02:10:28,582
[SPEAKER_06]: My next comment or question has to do with the use table and allowed usages, which we got into a little bit.

1364
02:10:31,805 --> 02:10:42,895
[SPEAKER_06]: I wonder if there was some sort of rubric used in deciding what uses are yes, what uses are no, what uses are ZBA.

1365
02:10:42,915 --> 02:10:51,923
[SPEAKER_06]: Because for example, I noticed that Makerspace and Work Only Artist Studio is yes, yes, yes.

1366
02:10:53,064 --> 02:10:56,447
[SPEAKER_06]: But if I want to run a carpentry shop, it's no.

1367
02:10:58,368 --> 02:11:03,612
[SPEAKER_06]: And, you know, so if I'm producing wooden sculptures, I'm okay.

1368
02:11:04,472 --> 02:11:08,275
[SPEAKER_06]: If I'm making designer furniture, maybe I'm running a carpentry shop.

1369
02:11:08,375 --> 02:11:09,776
[SPEAKER_06]: I mean, is there a rubric?

1370
02:11:10,176 --> 02:11:12,158
[SPEAKER_06]: I'm not trying to dwell on that specific point.

1371
02:11:12,798 --> 02:11:17,761
[SPEAKER_06]: I'm just trying to say that a lot of these uses are similar.

1372
02:11:18,602 --> 02:11:22,825
[SPEAKER_06]: And so how did you decide what's yes and what's no and what's maybe?

1373
02:11:31,547 --> 02:11:31,988
[SPEAKER_17]: Thank you.

1374
02:11:32,649 --> 02:11:33,610
[SPEAKER_17]: Excellent question.

1375
02:11:33,750 --> 02:11:39,359
[SPEAKER_17]: In many cases we started with so all of these are coming from your existing table of uses.

1376
02:11:39,399 --> 02:11:46,410
[SPEAKER_17]: We are using your existing table of uses and we are trying to be consistent with what has been allowed in similar districts.

1377
02:11:46,870 --> 02:11:51,596
[SPEAKER_17]: What may be allowed in the current existing districts that are being replaced.

1378
02:11:52,417 --> 02:12:04,651
[SPEAKER_17]: I believe the carpentry shop may be classified as an industrial use and the maker spaces and artisanal spaces are up in the commercial uses so that would.

1379
02:12:07,113 --> 02:12:12,137
[SPEAKER_17]: That would be one reason why they would be different is the levels of intensity and how they're classified.

1380
02:12:12,817 --> 02:12:14,559
[SPEAKER_17]: Certainly we're happy to take a look at that.

1381
02:12:15,319 --> 02:12:29,651
[SPEAKER_17]: I would also say that one thing to think about if you were wanting to open up some of these other uses, certainly we've been talking about a few in this conversation, is to make sure that the definitions are separate from the standards.

1382
02:12:29,771 --> 02:12:32,053
[SPEAKER_17]: So, for example, we were talking earlier

1383
02:12:32,993 --> 02:12:38,339
[SPEAKER_17]: the conversation about whether or not to allow for privately run student dorms.

1384
02:12:38,779 --> 02:12:40,981
[SPEAKER_17]: You would have a definition of what that is.

1385
02:12:41,622 --> 02:12:54,054
[SPEAKER_17]: And then if you wanted to put standards on it, like the number of rooms or the annual licensing, I think that was mentioned, that should go into the youth standards section, which you already have for the historical conversion.

1386
02:12:54,648 --> 02:12:56,849
[SPEAKER_17]: and we're proposing for the drive-through pharmacy.

1387
02:12:56,929 --> 02:12:58,530
[SPEAKER_17]: So just a couple of other things.

1388
02:12:58,550 --> 02:13:13,259
[SPEAKER_17]: So for example, if you wanted to allow carpentry shops as a right, but you wanted to have some sort or even by site plan review or special permit, and you wanted to have some sort of limitation on that, you would want to consider adding use standards in.

1389
02:13:13,359 --> 02:13:19,202
[SPEAKER_17]: But I believe it's because a carpentry shop is classified as industrial in the existing table of uses.

1390
02:13:24,010 --> 02:13:27,451
[SPEAKER_06]: Are all these uses actually defined somewhere?

1391
02:13:30,792 --> 02:13:32,232
[SPEAKER_17]: Not all, many are.

1392
02:13:32,272 --> 02:13:38,274
[SPEAKER_17]: Certainly the new uses that we have added in over the past couple of zoning rounds, those are defined.

1393
02:13:38,314 --> 02:13:39,474
[SPEAKER_17]: That was part of what we did.

1394
02:13:39,554 --> 02:13:44,956
[SPEAKER_17]: But I don't know that every single use in the table of uses has been defined.

1395
02:13:47,096 --> 02:13:48,997
[SPEAKER_17]: Some of that would have been through the recodification.

1396
02:13:50,397 --> 02:13:52,598
[SPEAKER_06]: Because you know, there are these sort of anomalies.

1397
02:13:53,651 --> 02:13:57,815
[SPEAKER_06]: We want to give pharmacies drive-thru access but not eating places.

1398
02:14:00,799 --> 02:14:03,662
[SPEAKER_07]: I'm actually not a fan of the pharmacy drive-thru.

1399
02:14:03,682 --> 02:14:08,086
[SPEAKER_07]: I think it's suburban and this is an urban corridor.

1400
02:14:08,106 --> 02:14:09,688
[SPEAKER_07]: I just think it's a bad use of that.

1401
02:14:09,748 --> 02:14:11,070
[SPEAKER_07]: My preference is to make it go away.

1402
02:14:13,072 --> 02:14:14,093
[SPEAKER_06]: Let's see what else I got.

1403
02:14:22,577 --> 02:14:29,880
[SPEAKER_06]: Oh, I just want to join with Doug in his concern about preserving historic neighborhoods.

1404
02:14:31,320 --> 02:14:39,383
[SPEAKER_06]: And I'm not approaching it from the point of view of all these buildings have historic significance.

1405
02:14:40,564 --> 02:14:45,005
[SPEAKER_06]: I'm just approaching it from the point of view of being a fan of older housing.

1406
02:14:45,746 --> 02:14:46,606
[SPEAKER_06]: And why is that?

1407
02:14:46,726 --> 02:14:48,427
[SPEAKER_06]: It's not out of sentimental reasons.

1408
02:14:49,429 --> 02:14:55,932
[SPEAKER_06]: In fact, a huge portion of the housing in Medford has been here a long time.

1409
02:14:56,033 --> 02:14:57,733
[SPEAKER_06]: Most of it was built before 1950.

1410
02:14:59,534 --> 02:15:04,817
[SPEAKER_06]: These are buildings that are much less expensive to buy than new construction.

1411
02:15:06,498 --> 02:15:11,080
[SPEAKER_06]: When I bought my house, it's like five bedrooms.

1412
02:15:11,100 --> 02:15:13,922
[SPEAKER_06]: It wasn't in great shape, but it was perfectly livable.

1413
02:15:14,860 --> 02:15:19,662
[SPEAKER_06]: But for only maybe another 25% more, I could have bought a tiny condo.

1414
02:15:20,822 --> 02:15:25,064
[SPEAKER_06]: But I chose to buy the old house because that was my preference.

1415
02:15:25,644 --> 02:15:28,245
[SPEAKER_06]: And at the time, I thought I needed the space.

1416
02:15:30,886 --> 02:15:34,347
[SPEAKER_06]: I don't know what I was planning to do with it, but I thought it was a great idea.

1417
02:15:34,367 --> 02:15:41,890
[SPEAKER_06]: I'm just saying that when those three deckers we were talking about,

1418
02:15:43,183 --> 02:16:00,891
[SPEAKER_06]: When they get torn down, and they will because we know about Adam Smith's invisible hand, the idea is that in a capitalist, profit-driven country, society, the most economic use of an asset will be discovered and taken advantage of.

1419
02:16:02,151 --> 02:16:07,034
[SPEAKER_06]: If you can make more money building houses than growing wheat, you're going to build houses.

1420
02:16:07,874 --> 02:16:12,036
[SPEAKER_06]: If you can make more money tearing down the triple-decker and putting up condos, you'll do that.

1421
02:16:12,868 --> 02:16:21,616
[SPEAKER_06]: And all over Medford, I've seen examples of where modest houses have been torn down and replaced by million dollar plus condos.

1422
02:16:22,537 --> 02:16:26,260
[SPEAKER_06]: So you're not just adding density, you're gentrifying when you do that.

1423
02:16:27,681 --> 02:16:29,723
[SPEAKER_06]: And I think that's something we need to keep in mind.

1424
02:16:32,005 --> 02:16:35,448
[SPEAKER_06]: That's all I have at the moment, except I wanna ask a question.

1425
02:16:35,988 --> 02:16:37,770
[SPEAKER_06]: Is this our last chance, really?

1426
02:16:38,458 --> 02:16:39,239
[SPEAKER_06]: To influence?

1427
02:16:39,779 --> 02:16:40,300
[SPEAKER_06]: No, we're continuing.

1428
02:16:40,320 --> 02:16:42,282
[SPEAKER_20]: We're continuing to next Thursday, June 11th.

1429
02:16:42,322 --> 02:16:45,885
[SPEAKER_06]: No, I'm just talking about to make more suggestions for changes.

1430
02:16:48,107 --> 02:16:49,248
[SPEAKER_20]: I mean, no.

1431
02:16:49,688 --> 02:16:51,169
[SPEAKER_07]: Okay.

1432
02:16:51,790 --> 02:16:59,237
[SPEAKER_07]: I mean, we have a menu that Zach is developing of, I hope, that is consensus on this list of potential changes.

1433
02:17:00,042 --> 02:17:09,548
[SPEAKER_07]: But we have to see that, and I think if Medford Square was the precedent, it was more than one bite at the apple to make sure we got it right.

1434
02:17:10,269 --> 02:17:10,829
[SPEAKER_06]: I remember.

1435
02:17:11,509 --> 02:17:12,170
[SPEAKER_07]: I'm sure you do.

1436
02:17:12,470 --> 02:17:12,630
[SPEAKER_07]: OK.

1437
02:17:12,670 --> 02:17:23,097
[SPEAKER_20]: Yeah, I think the idea is to try to give some direction tonight, see the response to that direction, and then consider that if it's great, then

1438
02:17:24,035 --> 02:17:27,936
[SPEAKER_20]: Maybe it's one more meeting if we need to go back one more time and there's a further.

1439
02:17:27,976 --> 02:17:31,836
[SPEAKER_07]: And keep in mind that not a single person in the public has had a chance to speak yet, right?

1440
02:17:31,876 --> 02:17:34,837
[SPEAKER_07]: So we really, I want to start the next meeting.

1441
02:17:34,957 --> 02:17:42,638
[SPEAKER_07]: I feel like we have to start with more public comment as soon as possible in the next meeting because we're on two and a half plus hours and we haven't heard from anyone yet.

1442
02:17:43,058 --> 02:17:47,599
[SPEAKER_07]: So I don't want to cut off that avenue either because I feel like great ideas can come from anywhere.

1443
02:17:48,159 --> 02:17:49,499
[SPEAKER_07]: So I'll sign off for now.

1444
02:17:50,640 --> 02:17:51,340
[SPEAKER_07]: You got the hint, huh?

1445
02:17:52,280 --> 02:17:52,660
[SPEAKER_07]: Oh, hold on.

1446
02:17:55,203 --> 02:18:06,770
[SPEAKER_16]: Quickly, very quickly, the Community Development Board received many, many public comments by email.

1447
02:18:06,930 --> 02:18:07,971
[SPEAKER_16]: They came in today.

1448
02:18:07,991 --> 02:18:11,073
[SPEAKER_16]: I had to work today.

1449
02:18:11,093 --> 02:18:12,393
[SPEAKER_16]: I have a job.

1450
02:18:12,413 --> 02:18:19,017
[SPEAKER_16]: I just can't go through all of those in a very meaningful way and consider the comments that came in.

1451
02:18:20,299 --> 02:18:31,976
[SPEAKER_16]: happy that the public comment, you know, we will hopefully need to extend that so we can make a very thoughtful, give the thoughtful approach of the comments that we received and how we develop the zoning.

1452
02:18:31,996 --> 02:18:34,800
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you, Dina.

1453
02:18:35,777 --> 02:18:38,780
[SPEAKER_07]: Speaking of public comments, I think it's time to open it up.

1454
02:18:38,940 --> 02:18:45,327
[SPEAKER_07]: So I think we're going to start with the people in the room since they've been here for two and a half hours, at least one or two people, and then we'll have some people online.

1455
02:18:45,908 --> 02:18:47,389
[SPEAKER_07]: Please give your name and address for the record.

1456
02:18:47,630 --> 02:18:51,954
[SPEAKER_07]: I think we want to be generous with the three minutes because I think people waited a long time.

1457
02:18:52,034 --> 02:18:55,398
[SPEAKER_07]: So try to keep it reasonable, but please go ahead and name and address for the record.

1458
02:18:56,718 --> 02:18:59,780
[SPEAKER_20]: I am gonna start the timer and we tend to alternate between in person.

1459
02:18:59,840 --> 02:19:00,100
[SPEAKER_20]: Okay.

1460
02:19:00,360 --> 02:19:01,321
[SPEAKER_20]: We'll do that.

1461
02:19:01,401 --> 02:19:02,521
[SPEAKER_20]: Give us one second.

1462
02:19:04,222 --> 02:19:04,702
[SPEAKER_07]: What's the number?

1463
02:19:06,343 --> 02:19:06,623
[SPEAKER_20]: Nine.

1464
02:19:07,104 --> 02:19:08,204
[SPEAKER_20]: They have to get a microphone.

1465
02:19:12,487 --> 02:19:13,167
[SPEAKER_07]: Mike would be good.

1466
02:19:14,868 --> 02:19:15,248
[SPEAKER_08]: Thank you.

1467
02:19:16,909 --> 02:19:18,630
[SPEAKER_08]: Patricia Dougherty, 190 High Street.

1468
02:19:18,670 --> 02:19:20,651
[SPEAKER_08]: I'll try to go through these points very quickly.

1469
02:19:22,499 --> 02:19:27,783
[SPEAKER_08]: Two people who were sitting with me asked me to add their comments, so I'll do that first.

1470
02:19:28,383 --> 02:19:41,932
[SPEAKER_08]: One woman lives on Burgadave and she was wondering if you could have a site visit, both the city council and the board, because it is a very good example of they back up to the Cummings building and what it did to their neighborhood.

1471
02:19:42,372 --> 02:19:48,994
[SPEAKER_08]: Also, they are now looking at the new Tough Storm going up, and it's another monstrosity.

1472
02:19:50,255 --> 02:19:56,557
[SPEAKER_08]: The Green Line took away all their greenery already, so that's her main request, and I think it's a really good idea.

1473
02:19:59,018 --> 02:20:12,745
[SPEAKER_08]: The other person mentioned traffic, density and everything else that some of you were taking consideration of and I want to thank you very much because it sounds like there's been some common sense and it was greatly needed.

1474
02:20:12,805 --> 02:20:16,267
[SPEAKER_08]: People are really, really nervous about the density and about the height.

1475
02:20:17,067 --> 02:20:19,869
[SPEAKER_08]: You know that from last summer from the uproar that took place.

1476
02:20:19,909 --> 02:20:25,572
[SPEAKER_08]: This is why you're sitting here again a year later because last year the residents did not want that to go through.

1477
02:20:26,092 --> 02:20:27,293
[SPEAKER_08]: Okay, now these are my points.

1478
02:20:30,174 --> 02:20:39,760
[SPEAKER_08]: Sort of going backwards, I heard some people interpreting what I would consider to be the law or statues, and I think they shouldn't be doing that, but I think you're stuck.

1479
02:20:39,800 --> 02:20:41,040
[SPEAKER_08]: You don't have a city solicitor.

1480
02:20:41,421 --> 02:20:44,302
[SPEAKER_08]: I implore you to ask the mayor to appoint a city solicitor.

1481
02:20:44,702 --> 02:20:48,985
[SPEAKER_08]: I frankly don't know how you're passing ordinances because the charter is very clear.

1482
02:20:49,585 --> 02:20:54,288
[SPEAKER_08]: So arguably, you need a city solicitor to sign off on any ordinance you pass.

1483
02:20:55,586 --> 02:20:58,608
[SPEAKER_08]: And outside law firm doesn't have the authority to do that.

1484
02:20:59,409 --> 02:21:04,272
[SPEAKER_08]: KP law firm had made it very clear a number of times that they represent the mayor only.

1485
02:21:04,292 --> 02:21:06,794
[SPEAKER_08]: Okay, back to the zoning.

1486
02:21:10,617 --> 02:21:18,643
[SPEAKER_08]: It was mentioned by a board member that it would be, she wanted density to allow

1487
02:21:19,195 --> 02:21:20,476
[SPEAKER_08]: I don't think that's a bad thing.

1488
02:21:20,536 --> 02:21:22,097
[SPEAKER_08]: I think it's a good thing.

1489
02:21:33,934 --> 02:21:36,276
[SPEAKER_08]: buildings and all the things that you mentioned.

1490
02:21:37,216 --> 02:21:48,044
[SPEAKER_08]: The other thing is that one of the team members over here mentioned that if you own property, you don't have to build up.

1491
02:21:48,505 --> 02:21:49,926
[SPEAKER_08]: You can just stay as it is.

1492
02:21:50,286 --> 02:21:50,926
[SPEAKER_08]: That's true.

1493
02:21:51,867 --> 02:21:58,512
[SPEAKER_08]: But if you're all of a sudden surrounded by five, six, and seven, eight stories, you're more likely to sell your property.

1494
02:21:59,592 --> 02:22:01,014
[SPEAKER_08]: These aren't blighted neighborhoods.

1495
02:22:01,554 --> 02:22:10,422
[SPEAKER_08]: These are well-maintained homes and these people care about their properties and we have a responsibility to make sure that we don't allow that to happen to them.

1496
02:22:11,824 --> 02:22:15,367
[SPEAKER_08]: With regards to the student dorms, I sat on this council for many years.

1497
02:22:15,992 --> 02:22:22,217
[SPEAKER_08]: a long time ago, and Tufts would come in front of us often and ask for help in building a dorm.

1498
02:22:22,857 --> 02:22:29,782
[SPEAKER_08]: Because of the Dover Amendment, of course, they get to build their dorms, but they often worked with us because they didn't want to offend us.

1499
02:22:30,162 --> 02:22:36,006
[SPEAKER_08]: We had a vice president of Tufts who was the community development liaison.

1500
02:22:36,066 --> 02:22:38,968
[SPEAKER_08]: I don't see anyone here doing that on a regular basis.

1501
02:22:39,789 --> 02:22:44,293
[SPEAKER_08]: But I can tell you that at least three, if not four, new dorms have been built.

1502
02:22:44,813 --> 02:22:48,096
[SPEAKER_08]: It didn't alleviate the problem in the Hillside neighborhood at all.

1503
02:22:48,557 --> 02:22:54,322
[SPEAKER_08]: All it did, and that was what they promised, no more parties, no more cars, no more beer cans on lawns.

1504
02:22:55,213 --> 02:23:05,224
[SPEAKER_08]: It didn't help because all Tufts did was increase their enrollment, and if you look at the numbers, you'll see that that happened because they had the dorms.

1505
02:23:05,584 --> 02:23:12,932
[SPEAKER_08]: Having been an upperclassman at one point, not at Tufts, and my kids doing the same thing, and many nieces and nephews doing it now,

1506
02:23:13,941 --> 02:23:16,562
[SPEAKER_08]: As you know, upperclassmen don't like to stay in a dorm.

1507
02:23:16,902 --> 02:23:18,963
[SPEAKER_08]: They move out to apartments, and they always will.

1508
02:23:20,023 --> 02:23:25,605
[SPEAKER_08]: So that's so much for adding 400 to 500 rooms for a private dorm.

1509
02:23:31,587 --> 02:23:33,428
[SPEAKER_20]: We're at about four minutes, just FYI.

1510
02:23:33,766 --> 02:23:36,347
[SPEAKER_08]: Well, I did take up that first minute with the other two people.

1511
02:23:38,548 --> 02:23:40,708
[SPEAKER_08]: It was also said in my last point is this one.

1512
02:23:40,988 --> 02:23:47,851
[SPEAKER_08]: It was mentioned over here that in one of the zoning changes, it would allow property owners to invest in their property without a variance.

1513
02:23:48,651 --> 02:23:51,492
[SPEAKER_08]: Well, zoning is to protect the property owner.

1514
02:23:52,503 --> 02:23:57,669
[SPEAKER_08]: And if you remove that, then the neighborhood doesn't have that protection of zoning.

1515
02:23:57,990 --> 02:24:02,475
[SPEAKER_08]: And you certainly can invest in your property without going outside the zoning code.

1516
02:24:03,377 --> 02:24:04,958
[SPEAKER_08]: So I ask you to please consider that.

1517
02:24:05,419 --> 02:24:06,260
[SPEAKER_08]: Thank you so much.

1518
02:24:06,580 --> 02:24:08,623
[SPEAKER_08]: And I don't know if this is possible, but maybe.

1519
02:24:09,664 --> 02:24:19,449
[SPEAKER_08]: Since we, and I can't speak to everyone else here, had already read the materials, gone through stuff online, watched the meeting the other night, we already heard all this.

1520
02:24:20,270 --> 02:24:28,835
[SPEAKER_08]: And maybe it's possible to let the people come up, since they kind of already know what they want to say, and do it and leave, and then you two boards can talk all night long if you want.

1521
02:24:29,515 --> 02:24:29,875
[SPEAKER_08]: Thank you.

1522
02:24:30,035 --> 02:24:30,736
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you very much.

1523
02:24:30,756 --> 02:24:31,216
[SPEAKER_07]: Appreciate it.

1524
02:24:31,376 --> 02:24:34,378
[SPEAKER_07]: I'm going to go next online to Dean if you could.

1525
02:24:35,758 --> 02:24:36,759
[SPEAKER_07]: I've asked you to unmute.

1526
02:24:41,260 --> 02:24:43,562
[SPEAKER_19]: Do I have the wrong one?

1527
02:24:43,582 --> 02:24:43,682
[SPEAKER_19]: Hello.

1528
02:24:43,942 --> 02:24:45,583
[SPEAKER_19]: My name is Dean Tognarelli.

1529
02:24:45,603 --> 02:24:50,487
[SPEAKER_19]: I live on North Street in Medford, a lifelong Medford resident.

1530
02:24:51,248 --> 02:24:57,713
[SPEAKER_19]: I've been looking at some of the images and the max height and how big things can be.

1531
02:24:57,733 --> 02:25:04,157
[SPEAKER_19]: I just want to say I think it's too much, too big, and way too many all at once.

1532
02:25:04,978 --> 02:25:09,842
[SPEAKER_19]: I know this has opened up to public comment and people get to weigh in.

1533
02:25:10,667 --> 02:25:14,749
[SPEAKER_19]: on what their thoughts are and what the benefits could be for the community or not.

1534
02:25:15,730 --> 02:25:18,271
[SPEAKER_19]: I think everybody probably has some good intentions.

1535
02:25:18,551 --> 02:25:34,398
[SPEAKER_19]: I would say that I believe people that live closer, maybe their opinion should be weighed slightly more than someone that might be two miles away, not impacted by increased traffic and problems.

1536
02:25:36,019 --> 02:25:39,501
[SPEAKER_19]: I heard comments, people saying that we have the appetite

1537
02:25:40,008 --> 02:25:54,515
[SPEAKER_19]: For more development with density, I would say not if you live right next door, not if you're hidden in the shadow of a giant building, not if you have traffic for days or weeks or months upon end.

1538
02:25:55,298 --> 02:26:07,486
[SPEAKER_19]: If you do live in the area and you do like it, it could be, maybe not always, but it could be, maybe you can now sell your property, benefit, make a lot of money and leave.

1539
02:26:07,867 --> 02:26:10,028
[SPEAKER_19]: So maybe you would be a fan of that.

1540
02:26:11,089 --> 02:26:20,375
[SPEAKER_19]: If this zoning is passed and I heard other people say, you know, there's certain zoning now, but it's not enticing people to really develop the property.

1541
02:26:21,142 --> 02:26:31,231
[SPEAKER_19]: If passed, it sounds like a lot hope that this will kickstart some development, some projects, and some increased tax revenue.

1542
02:26:31,891 --> 02:26:35,514
[SPEAKER_19]: Is there any limit to how many could happen at once?

1543
02:26:36,315 --> 02:26:48,205
[SPEAKER_19]: Could something happen over in the area behind the Whole Foods or where the Life Science was at the same time that the Hillside hardware is being worked on?

1544
02:26:48,683 --> 02:26:54,105
[SPEAKER_19]: Could it maybe take an hour or two to get from where I am on North Street to Memphis Square?

1545
02:26:54,665 --> 02:26:59,467
[SPEAKER_19]: Is it possible that it could be more than anyone can handle?

1546
02:26:59,767 --> 02:27:04,928
[SPEAKER_19]: And once they approve a project, it is now too late to stop?

1547
02:27:06,029 --> 02:27:12,151
[SPEAKER_19]: I think this is maybe gonna be my attempt at humor, but I really don't find it that funny.

1548
02:27:12,471 --> 02:27:16,152
[SPEAKER_19]: When we did the Green Line extension,

1549
02:27:16,826 --> 02:27:19,248
[SPEAKER_19]: There were rats running up the street.

1550
02:27:19,588 --> 02:27:23,230
[SPEAKER_19]: I mean, like an ungodly wave, I could not believe.

1551
02:27:24,111 --> 02:27:41,441
[SPEAKER_19]: Has anyone spent all the time in zoning, planning and everything else to think about all of the disruption to the ground in the area and how, as a community, we should handle what I would say would be a large pile of rats, might be a huge pile of rats, could be just a few rats.

1552
02:27:42,022 --> 02:27:44,023
[SPEAKER_19]: Whatever they are, I'd like to know

1553
02:27:44,762 --> 02:27:46,503
[SPEAKER_19]: how we think we can address that.

1554
02:27:46,663 --> 02:27:52,005
[SPEAKER_19]: Is someone standing up at the end of my street with a giant net, scooping them up before they run up the street?

1555
02:27:53,545 --> 02:27:56,506
[SPEAKER_19]: We had composting added not too long ago.

1556
02:27:57,147 --> 02:28:00,988
[SPEAKER_19]: Is there some special bucket that someone thinks they can drop off at my house?

1557
02:28:01,628 --> 02:28:13,593
[SPEAKER_19]: I can catch them in a barrel of water and dump them in that, or I'd be happy to bring them down and drop them off somewhere towards City Hall or wherever the other decisions are being made that aren't working out to my advantage.

1558
02:28:14,678 --> 02:28:16,859
[SPEAKER_19]: That's all I have to say.

1559
02:28:18,721 --> 02:28:19,361
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you very much.

1560
02:28:19,401 --> 02:28:19,921
[SPEAKER_07]: Appreciate it.

1561
02:28:20,242 --> 02:28:22,843
[SPEAKER_07]: Is there anyone else in the room who would like to speak?

1562
02:28:23,104 --> 02:28:26,706
[SPEAKER_07]: Please come on up and your name and address for the record, please.

1563
02:28:30,803 --> 02:28:32,324
[SPEAKER_04]: Hi, my name is Laura Longsworth.

1564
02:28:32,405 --> 02:28:35,808
[SPEAKER_04]: I also live on North Street, right on the edge of BA3.

1565
02:28:37,469 --> 02:28:46,057
[SPEAKER_04]: I'm here mostly to just advocate for removing fraternities and sororities as a potential use in BA3.

1566
02:28:47,578 --> 02:28:50,921
[SPEAKER_04]: I lived in Medford for 15 years, but I'm a native of Amherst.

1567
02:28:52,262 --> 02:29:08,640
[SPEAKER_04]: Child of a college president, and I went through many years of discussions about the abolition of fraternities at Amherst College, and I had way too much privy to the variabilities of fraternity life on campus, and I really appreciate living near a college.

1568
02:29:08,720 --> 02:29:10,362
[SPEAKER_04]: I always have, my entire life.

1569
02:29:11,143 --> 02:29:27,634
[SPEAKER_04]: I sort of enjoy my neighbors in training, as I call them, otherwise known as students, and yet I spend a lot of time walking around on Tufts and I see what's going on with the fraternities and the partying and so forth, and it's sort of young people behavior, but I think it's along the lines of why would we invite this?

1570
02:29:28,595 --> 02:29:39,499
[SPEAKER_04]: into our neighborhood, especially in a moment when I know Tufts has been wrestling with dealing with the fraternities and the sororities and kind of trying to tamp down on some of the behavior.

1571
02:29:40,399 --> 02:29:44,821
[SPEAKER_04]: And then there's also just the element of it being essentially a private club.

1572
02:29:45,621 --> 02:29:49,943
[SPEAKER_04]: Like we're trying to build housing and yet it's a possibility of a private club that

1573
02:29:50,643 --> 02:30:11,539
[SPEAKER_04]: would be, I think the language right now says it would have to be recognized by Tufts, so it's a private club recognized by a private entity, and we don't have participation in what recognition means, and we don't, we know Tufts has unrecognized some fraternities, and we don't know what that means then, that there's a private club not recognized by the private entity.

1574
02:30:11,899 --> 02:30:13,040
[SPEAKER_04]: Anyway, I think you get my point.

1575
02:30:13,320 --> 02:30:14,481
[SPEAKER_04]: It's potentially a lot of,

1576
02:30:16,262 --> 02:30:27,231
[SPEAKER_04]: disruption and I actually did a little research and I can read you the long list of communities that have had either lawsuits or just major conflict with off-campus Greek life.

1577
02:30:27,251 --> 02:30:28,872
[SPEAKER_04]: Do you want me to read the list?

1578
02:30:29,453 --> 02:30:31,214
[SPEAKER_04]: It's like 18 communities.

1579
02:30:31,334 --> 02:30:35,277
[SPEAKER_07]: I would like you to submit it actually as a written comment so it's in the record.

1580
02:30:35,377 --> 02:30:35,597
[SPEAKER_04]: Okay.

1581
02:30:35,718 --> 02:30:36,818
[SPEAKER_07]: I think that would be important.

1582
02:30:36,898 --> 02:30:38,820
[SPEAKER_07]: I appreciate that information.

1583
02:30:39,020 --> 02:30:39,460
[SPEAKER_04]: Okay.

1584
02:30:39,661 --> 02:30:40,421
[SPEAKER_04]: I will submit that.

1585
02:30:40,441 --> 02:30:45,265
[SPEAKER_04]: Yeah, I think those are my main points about

1586
02:30:45,926 --> 02:30:57,138
[SPEAKER_04]: And I think on the, you know, just on the issue of the purpose built student housing, I know we have a student housing issue in Medford.

1587
02:30:58,239 --> 02:31:01,362
[SPEAKER_04]: I, you know, you can see in our neighborhood there's a mix.

1588
02:31:01,503 --> 02:31:02,904
[SPEAKER_04]: I find it an interesting mix.

1589
02:31:03,004 --> 02:31:05,507
[SPEAKER_04]: And I know that there are problem houses and problem areas.

1590
02:31:06,808 --> 02:31:10,493
[SPEAKER_04]: that people who have lived there longer than I have probably feel that more.

1591
02:31:11,154 --> 02:31:18,442
[SPEAKER_04]: I really question the premise that purpose-built student housing in BA3 is a solution to this issue.

1592
02:31:18,903 --> 02:31:20,044
[SPEAKER_04]: It's far from campus.

1593
02:31:20,785 --> 02:31:25,792
[SPEAKER_04]: Students seem to be more concentrated in off-campus housing right around campus.

1594
02:31:26,532 --> 02:31:37,699
[SPEAKER_04]: I don't really know, I would love to see the evidence that if we built purpose built student housing, that they will actually live there instead of living in Hillside.

1595
02:31:38,159 --> 02:31:43,402
[SPEAKER_04]: I just don't buy it, basically, and I don't think we should assume that's what would happen.

1596
02:31:43,762 --> 02:31:47,345
[SPEAKER_04]: I think we need to have it proven, and I actually did also do some other research.

1597
02:31:48,085 --> 02:31:56,290
[SPEAKER_04]: which shows that owner occupancy actually declines often with purpose-built student housing because people just basically don't really want to live near it.

1598
02:31:57,071 --> 02:32:01,353
[SPEAKER_04]: So I think we have kind of an amazing opportunity with BA3.

1599
02:32:04,235 --> 02:32:07,717
[SPEAKER_04]: The potential to do something really cool as a city is there.

1600
02:32:08,457 --> 02:32:13,500
[SPEAKER_04]: And I just really hope what happened in the seaport doesn't happen in Medford.

1601
02:32:13,960 --> 02:32:24,505
[SPEAKER_04]: And my view of the seaport is it was a parking lot, and then the city just let developers build what they wanted instead of having a really nice, solid, coherent plan.

1602
02:32:25,105 --> 02:32:27,466
[SPEAKER_04]: And I don't know who among us goes to the seaport.

1603
02:32:28,707 --> 02:32:30,548
[SPEAKER_04]: You can look at glass or buy Lululemon, I guess.

1604
02:32:30,648 --> 02:32:36,690
[SPEAKER_04]: But it's just like not a very, if you think about the potential, it's not a very interesting place.

1605
02:32:37,270 --> 02:32:44,112
[SPEAKER_04]: And I really hope that BA3 becomes an interesting place and that it's made for people who actually would like to live there.

1606
02:32:44,752 --> 02:32:46,733
[SPEAKER_04]: And I appreciate the comments about shrinking the height.

1607
02:32:46,993 --> 02:32:48,074
[SPEAKER_04]: I think that's right on.

1608
02:32:48,774 --> 02:32:50,474
[SPEAKER_04]: And I would actually like to see more green space.

1609
02:32:50,494 --> 02:32:53,515
[SPEAKER_04]: I think 90% density is way, way, way too high.

1610
02:32:53,916 --> 02:32:55,136
[SPEAKER_04]: And we need some grass.

1611
02:32:55,156 --> 02:32:56,516
[SPEAKER_07]: All right.

1612
02:32:56,596 --> 02:32:56,917
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you.

1613
02:32:56,957 --> 02:32:57,537
[SPEAKER_07]: Great comments.

1614
02:32:57,577 --> 02:32:57,877
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you.

1615
02:33:01,107 --> 02:33:02,369
[SPEAKER_07]: Anybody else in the room?

1616
02:33:02,670 --> 02:33:04,112
[SPEAKER_07]: Otherwise, I'm going to go back to online.

1617
02:33:06,596 --> 02:33:06,757
[SPEAKER_07]: Yes.

1618
02:33:09,641 --> 02:33:10,721
[SPEAKER_00]: My name is Anita Nagum.

1619
02:33:10,901 --> 02:33:12,402
[SPEAKER_00]: I live at 9 Norton Avenue.

1620
02:33:13,343 --> 02:33:23,448
[SPEAKER_00]: And I agree with most of Chairman Carr's comments, but I do take issue with one in particular, the height along, that you think the height along the tracks can be big.

1621
02:33:24,349 --> 02:33:28,211
[SPEAKER_00]: I live on the other side of the tracks, along North Street, just off of North Street.

1622
02:33:30,012 --> 02:33:34,794
[SPEAKER_00]: It seems to me that you have not really considered the consequences of building there on our side.

1623
02:33:35,294 --> 02:33:44,018
[SPEAKER_00]: When 200 Boston Avenue, 10, 15 years ago, wanted to build an extra two stories, they were four stories originally, they wanted to add two.

1624
02:33:44,619 --> 02:33:45,539
[SPEAKER_00]: The neighborhood objected.

1625
02:33:47,240 --> 02:33:47,720
[SPEAKER_00]: They were built.

1626
02:33:48,840 --> 02:33:52,602
[SPEAKER_00]: Now there are labs on that floor with lights on all night.

1627
02:33:52,802 --> 02:33:54,463
[SPEAKER_00]: They shine into my house.

1628
02:33:54,863 --> 02:33:58,585
[SPEAKER_00]: There is a huge privacy issue, and I'm not even as close as many people are.

1629
02:34:00,434 --> 02:34:07,776
[SPEAKER_00]: I also take issue with your characterization of Walkland Court being a good example of the step down.

1630
02:34:08,397 --> 02:34:10,477
[SPEAKER_00]: If you look at it from Auburn Street, it is.

1631
02:34:11,237 --> 02:34:13,978
[SPEAKER_00]: If you look at it from the side, it is anything but.

1632
02:34:15,099 --> 02:34:23,921
[SPEAKER_00]: The neighbors, again, I'm almost in line with where the new six-story buildings are going to be between that and this 200 Boston Avenue.

1633
02:34:24,521 --> 02:34:29,083
[SPEAKER_00]: We did not want another building of that height on our side of the tracks.

1634
02:34:30,125 --> 02:34:36,028
[SPEAKER_00]: It makes a very big difference and that six story building is going to be right up against North Street.

1635
02:34:36,569 --> 02:34:41,411
[SPEAKER_00]: There are two story houses across the street on North Street.

1636
02:34:41,852 --> 02:34:46,154
[SPEAKER_00]: There are not only single family but single story buildings on the same block.

1637
02:34:47,820 --> 02:34:48,760
[SPEAKER_00]: Not acceptable.

1638
02:34:50,961 --> 02:34:57,843
[SPEAKER_00]: I also those are all the issues that I take all the things I took issue with you with your comments.

1639
02:34:57,883 --> 02:35:02,645
[SPEAKER_00]: There was another comment by another person that just because it's zoned for something doesn't mean it's going to be built.

1640
02:35:03,645 --> 02:35:07,086
[SPEAKER_00]: Don't zone it unless you expect it to be built.

1641
02:35:08,446 --> 02:35:11,067
[SPEAKER_00]: Once the zoning is in the cat is out of the bag.

1642
02:35:11,587 --> 02:35:11,947
[SPEAKER_00]: That's it.

1643
02:35:14,540 --> 02:35:16,362
[SPEAKER_00]: I really object to that characterization.

1644
02:35:16,442 --> 02:35:18,784
[SPEAKER_00]: Oh, we can have it built for this, but it probably won't be built.

1645
02:35:19,485 --> 02:35:20,245
[SPEAKER_00]: It's too late then.

1646
02:35:21,607 --> 02:35:28,213
[SPEAKER_00]: I also strenuously object to purpose-built student housing being put on the Elizabeth Grady site.

1647
02:35:30,200 --> 02:35:37,806
[SPEAKER_00]: student housing does not belong in the middle of a residential and small commercial business district.

1648
02:35:38,627 --> 02:35:40,528
[SPEAKER_00]: Tufts has a lot of room on its campus.

1649
02:35:41,229 --> 02:35:45,852
[SPEAKER_00]: If they want to build dorms, they have a lot more open space than we do in Hillside.

1650
02:35:48,754 --> 02:35:50,596
[SPEAKER_00]: That is not the place to put it.

1651
02:35:51,617 --> 02:35:55,700
[SPEAKER_00]: And just one other comment about the shadows that will be

1652
02:35:57,717 --> 02:36:00,838
[SPEAKER_00]: or the regulations about shadows that will be included in the zoning.

1653
02:36:02,958 --> 02:36:06,178
[SPEAKER_00]: My understanding is that there is a requirement for two hours of daylight.

1654
02:36:06,979 --> 02:36:08,359
[SPEAKER_00]: That is pretty minimal.

1655
02:36:09,579 --> 02:36:11,639
[SPEAKER_00]: And quite frankly, I think that should be increased.

1656
02:36:12,059 --> 02:36:16,820
[SPEAKER_00]: But it should be stipulated that that will be measured on the shortest day of the year.

1657
02:36:17,780 --> 02:36:22,241
[SPEAKER_00]: Do not do that on June 21st and say, oh, well, in June you get two hours.

1658
02:36:23,121 --> 02:36:25,302
[SPEAKER_00]: The sunlight in the winter is what matters more.

1659
02:36:26,522 --> 02:36:26,802
[SPEAKER_00]: Thank you.

1660
02:36:28,308 --> 02:36:28,568
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you.

1661
02:36:28,588 --> 02:36:29,729
[SPEAKER_07]: Appreciate that very much.

1662
02:36:30,969 --> 02:36:44,516
[SPEAKER_07]: I will say that I, I, I think we should, when I mentioned North, North Street and Boston have having those, your house should fall in that same category because it's, it's a, it's an abutting property, even though it's across the track.

1663
02:36:44,536 --> 02:36:45,377
[SPEAKER_07]: So I appreciate that.

1664
02:36:45,417 --> 02:36:46,277
[SPEAKER_07]: We'll take a look at that.

1665
02:36:46,337 --> 02:36:46,677
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you.

1666
02:36:47,718 --> 02:36:53,501
[SPEAKER_07]: We are going to switch to the, to Laurel Ruma who was next.

1667
02:36:53,521 --> 02:36:54,981
[SPEAKER_20]: We'll go to Laurel Ruma on Zoom.

1668
02:36:55,041 --> 02:36:57,123
[SPEAKER_20]: Laurel, name and address for the record, please.

1669
02:36:57,143 --> 02:36:57,963
[SPEAKER_20]: You'll have three minutes.

1670
02:36:58,647 --> 02:36:59,087
[SPEAKER_13]: Hi, everyone.

1671
02:36:59,107 --> 02:37:01,469
[SPEAKER_13]: I'm Laurel Ruma, 149 Burgett Avenue.

1672
02:37:01,949 --> 02:37:07,652
[SPEAKER_13]: And as you can see behind me, this is the Tufts dorm up on Boston Avenue.

1673
02:37:08,112 --> 02:37:12,435
[SPEAKER_13]: So I just really want to hit a number of points, and then I will write my comments in for sure.

1674
02:37:12,775 --> 02:37:14,596
[SPEAKER_13]: One is, I appreciate a good story.

1675
02:37:15,096 --> 02:37:16,677
[SPEAKER_13]: Hyperbole is real.

1676
02:37:17,218 --> 02:37:18,859
[SPEAKER_13]: There were not rats running up and down the streets.

1677
02:37:19,299 --> 02:37:26,103
[SPEAKER_13]: Not only did Tufts build their high rise here, the green lines in my backyard, this other dorm building's being built, the rat problem

1678
02:37:27,598 --> 02:37:37,508
[SPEAKER_13]: come on let's be realistic people when we talk about our city and what we see when construction happens because it's not not helpful to to say there's rats running up and down the streets.

1679
02:37:38,930 --> 02:37:49,421
[SPEAKER_13]: I really want to stress now listen I spent 12 years as the representative for the city of Medford on the Green Line extension and what rapid transit is is a definition that

1680
02:37:50,824 --> 02:37:56,833
[SPEAKER_13]: has been defined, and the Green Line station is rapid transit I'm sorry you don't take it all the time.

1681
02:37:57,153 --> 02:38:07,207
[SPEAKER_13]: There's a lot of us that do, clearly, because the sites have been done and the trains are full in the mornings the trains are full at night, and the buses also, you know, provide a lot of rapid transit options.

1682
02:38:08,580 --> 02:38:11,861
[SPEAKER_13]: This is not stuff we need to be legislating or litigating right here.

1683
02:38:11,901 --> 02:38:17,322
[SPEAKER_13]: This is stuff that is beyond the scope of what needs to be talked about in these discussions.

1684
02:38:17,802 --> 02:38:22,122
[SPEAKER_13]: And I really encourage both boards to really focus on what has to be done tonight.

1685
02:38:22,763 --> 02:38:26,423
[SPEAKER_13]: And it is ridiculous that we're only on our X number of meetings here.

1686
02:38:26,443 --> 02:38:30,704
[SPEAKER_13]: We only have so many meetings left and we're not getting to the heart of the matter.

1687
02:38:30,844 --> 02:38:34,325
[SPEAKER_13]: The heart of the matter is no fraternities and sororities should be zoned.

1688
02:38:34,745 --> 02:38:35,985
[SPEAKER_13]: Absolutely no private dorms.

1689
02:38:37,285 --> 02:38:49,317
[SPEAKER_13]: As said previously, those of us that live in the neighborhood don't want to live in a neighborhood that's not diverse, that's only full of dorms to serve either Tufts kids or any other kids in Boston.

1690
02:38:49,357 --> 02:38:50,478
[SPEAKER_13]: They can go live somewhere else.

1691
02:38:51,299 --> 02:38:51,519
[SPEAKER_13]: Listen.

1692
02:38:52,508 --> 02:39:02,092
[SPEAKER_13]: Tufts has publicly stated that their plan, their business plan is to put 75% of the students back on campus in housing.

1693
02:39:02,833 --> 02:39:11,077
[SPEAKER_13]: So, who's living in these private dorms, who's living in these fraternities and sororities, who's living in our neighborhoods anymore, if that actually does happen.

1694
02:39:12,522 --> 02:39:20,171
[SPEAKER_13]: We have to look at this ecosystem as something that encompasses a lot of other things and a lot of other factors.

1695
02:39:20,191 --> 02:39:23,714
[SPEAKER_13]: I know we're not talking about Tufts tonight, but let's be realistic.

1696
02:39:23,795 --> 02:39:27,278
[SPEAKER_13]: Tufts also owns a majority of the properties up and down Boston Avenue.

1697
02:39:27,699 --> 02:39:31,203
[SPEAKER_13]: And so when we talk about, oh, it wouldn't be great if this is what happens when developers come in.

1698
02:39:32,645 --> 02:39:34,266
[SPEAKER_13]: there's already a developer, they're already here.

1699
02:39:34,787 --> 02:39:35,307
[SPEAKER_13]: And guess what?

1700
02:39:35,547 --> 02:39:41,331
[SPEAKER_13]: There's such thing as Dover, and they do not have to necessarily abide by these zoning changes and rules.

1701
02:39:41,732 --> 02:39:43,173
[SPEAKER_13]: So let's think about that.

1702
02:39:43,573 --> 02:39:45,695
[SPEAKER_13]: The shadow study is a really important thing.

1703
02:39:46,375 --> 02:39:52,480
[SPEAKER_13]: I think we all object to six to eight stories being on the railroad side of the tracks, because you think the other side of Boston Ave is quaint.

1704
02:39:54,761 --> 02:39:59,005
[SPEAKER_13]: No offense chair car, but I mean, come on, like it either everybody,

1705
02:40:00,137 --> 02:40:04,380
[SPEAKER_13]: gets 10-story buildings, or no one should be getting 10-story buildings.

1706
02:40:04,500 --> 02:40:05,081
[SPEAKER_13]: But guess what?

1707
02:40:05,181 --> 02:40:06,702
[SPEAKER_13]: The cat's already out of the bag.

1708
02:40:07,082 --> 02:40:08,363
[SPEAKER_13]: We already have this in our neighborhood.

1709
02:40:08,723 --> 02:40:11,485
[SPEAKER_13]: We've now made the standard that this is what's acceptable.

1710
02:40:11,906 --> 02:40:12,947
[SPEAKER_13]: And I'm actually okay with that.

1711
02:40:13,507 --> 02:40:16,849
[SPEAKER_13]: Everyone should be exposed to the wonder of mixed-use

1712
02:40:17,710 --> 02:40:23,536
[SPEAKER_13]: will have lots of retail on the bottom, lots of people living up top, all sorts of different people of all sorts of different incomes.

1713
02:40:24,257 --> 02:40:27,320
[SPEAKER_13]: And whether you're a student or not and you're just a regular person, that's great.

1714
02:40:27,340 --> 02:40:29,823
[SPEAKER_13]: What we want is diverse options in housing here.

1715
02:40:31,945 --> 02:40:32,846
[SPEAKER_13]: And then lastly,

1716
02:40:35,168 --> 02:40:39,951
[SPEAKER_13]: You know, honestly, we can't have gas stations, because we have a high water table.

1717
02:40:40,331 --> 02:40:42,413
[SPEAKER_13]: These two things don't don't mix.

1718
02:40:42,953 --> 02:40:46,935
[SPEAKER_13]: So, I don't think we should actually zone for more gas stations.

1719
02:40:47,556 --> 02:40:53,479
[SPEAKER_13]: There's quite a few around here, they require such heavy regulation and specific needs.

1720
02:40:54,740 --> 02:41:02,464
[SPEAKER_13]: The water tables a real problem Burgett Avenue, talk to tough so tell you how much money they've already spent and trying to regulate their water table underneath all those fields.

1721
02:41:03,544 --> 02:41:08,146
[SPEAKER_13]: You know, listen, we all love our neighborhood, we understand it's changing.

1722
02:41:08,647 --> 02:41:11,348
[SPEAKER_13]: It's taken a lot of us a long time to get here.

1723
02:41:11,848 --> 02:41:13,029
[SPEAKER_13]: We have the green line now.

1724
02:41:13,350 --> 02:41:17,413
[SPEAKER_13]: We have this opportunity to expand in a really smart and excellent way.

1725
02:41:18,174 --> 02:41:24,801
[SPEAKER_13]: And I guess I'm more with Ari on this side, which is more building is better and we have a way to do it in a good way.

1726
02:41:25,321 --> 02:41:26,022
[SPEAKER_13]: So thank you.

1727
02:41:28,004 --> 02:41:28,564
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you, Laura.

1728
02:41:28,584 --> 02:41:29,105
[SPEAKER_07]: Appreciate it.

1729
02:41:30,907 --> 02:41:31,127
[SPEAKER_07]: Next.

1730
02:41:34,303 --> 02:41:38,884
[SPEAKER_09]: Mary Anna Ducey at 2 North Street in Medford.

1731
02:41:39,004 --> 02:41:50,188
[SPEAKER_09]: I have some comments, but the first thing I would like to say is that all of you should walk this neighborhood to put in perspective what I'm saying and why I'm saying it.

1732
02:41:50,228 --> 02:41:51,428
[SPEAKER_09]: All right.

1733
02:41:51,708 --> 02:41:54,429
[SPEAKER_09]: The first thing is the traffic on Boston Ave.

1734
02:41:55,070 --> 02:41:58,050
[SPEAKER_09]: From 4 to 6 most days, it's backed up.

1735
02:41:58,371 --> 02:42:02,212
[SPEAKER_09]: You have to wait for probably four or five changes of lights to get through Winter Street.

1736
02:42:03,212 --> 02:42:06,116
[SPEAKER_09]: On the other end, it's backed all the way up the hill, Winthrop Street.

1737
02:42:07,237 --> 02:42:09,219
[SPEAKER_09]: So there's a traffic problem here.

1738
02:42:10,761 --> 02:42:18,650
[SPEAKER_09]: There's already three storey houses on Boston Ave, in between North Street and Winthrop Street.

1739
02:42:19,151 --> 02:42:22,554
[SPEAKER_09]: And many of the houses don't have dryways, so the people have to park on the street.

1740
02:42:24,075 --> 02:42:30,518
[SPEAKER_09]: Most of the Boston Nav Houses are privately owned, but they're occupied by tough students.

1741
02:42:30,578 --> 02:42:34,019
[SPEAKER_09]: And I know that because I've gone around with petitions for the buses and so forth.

1742
02:42:34,280 --> 02:42:38,341
[SPEAKER_09]: And when I knock on doors, I find out there's tough students living there, which is OK.

1743
02:42:38,901 --> 02:42:42,683
[SPEAKER_09]: But they're not owner-occupied.

1744
02:42:42,703 --> 02:42:43,623
[SPEAKER_09]: They're mostly rentals.

1745
02:42:46,865 --> 02:42:53,692
[SPEAKER_09]: The Walkling Court redevelopment is going to house 300 to 350 people when it's completed.

1746
02:42:55,113 --> 02:43:07,266
[SPEAKER_09]: There are two six-story buildings along the track, as your illustration showed there, one four-story apartment building in the center, and several townhouses around the circumference that back up to the residential houses.

1747
02:43:09,388 --> 02:43:14,932
[SPEAKER_09]: The six-story buildings have the ground level is parking under the building.

1748
02:43:15,993 --> 02:43:16,994
[SPEAKER_09]: It's not below ground.

1749
02:43:17,034 --> 02:43:18,415
[SPEAKER_09]: It's on street level.

1750
02:43:21,497 --> 02:43:26,761
[SPEAKER_09]: Over the bridge between Marshall Street and Boston Ave, North Street is very narrow.

1751
02:43:27,762 --> 02:43:30,144
[SPEAKER_09]: There's only two lanes of traffic coming and going.

1752
02:43:30,164 --> 02:43:32,125
[SPEAKER_09]: You cannot park on either side of the street.

1753
02:43:34,767 --> 02:43:37,089
[SPEAKER_09]: The houses on Piggott Road, which is opposite

1754
02:43:38,577 --> 02:43:44,702
[SPEAKER_09]: the property, the Elizabeth Grady property, there are one story single family homes.

1755
02:43:46,763 --> 02:43:53,028
[SPEAKER_09]: Trucks are not allowed on North Street because trucks are not allowed on Route 16.

1756
02:43:53,128 --> 02:43:55,470
[SPEAKER_09]: So North Street is a truck route.

1757
02:43:55,630 --> 02:43:57,832
[SPEAKER_09]: What that means is that trucks

1758
02:43:58,472 --> 02:44:03,876
[SPEAKER_09]: have to come up West Street, up North Street, and on their way because they cannot go on Route 16.

1759
02:44:04,937 --> 02:44:11,341
[SPEAKER_09]: So when the trucks get to the Boston Ave and North Street intersection, it's pretty tight there if there's an 18-wheeler truck there.

1760
02:44:11,721 --> 02:44:17,745
[SPEAKER_09]: Plus, Whole Foods delivery trucks come frequently during the day to resupply the store.

1761
02:44:18,346 --> 02:44:20,367
[SPEAKER_09]: There are school buses that come up North Street.

1762
02:44:24,898 --> 02:44:29,376
[SPEAKER_09]: The current Boston Ave bus routes, my neighbor and I have been

1763
02:44:31,398 --> 02:44:35,901
[SPEAKER_09]: challenging the T for the last four years because they want to eliminate buses.

1764
02:44:36,402 --> 02:44:39,224
[SPEAKER_09]: So there's bus service today, but we've been fighting.

1765
02:44:39,244 --> 02:44:45,208
[SPEAKER_09]: Originally, they wanted to eliminate the 94 bus, which still might happen.

1766
02:44:45,848 --> 02:44:49,911
[SPEAKER_09]: The 80 bus was going to go on a one-hour schedule for part of the day.

1767
02:44:50,692 --> 02:44:56,336
[SPEAKER_09]: The 96 bus, the route is potentially going to change if it even stays here.

1768
02:45:02,702 --> 02:45:06,504
[SPEAKER_09]: Okay.

1769
02:45:06,524 --> 02:45:07,705
[SPEAKER_09]: I can't even read my notes here.

1770
02:45:08,425 --> 02:45:10,306
[SPEAKER_09]: All right.

1771
02:45:10,406 --> 02:45:19,192
[SPEAKER_09]: So, the lack of bus service will encourage more people, residents to have cars.

1772
02:45:19,372 --> 02:45:29,638
[SPEAKER_09]: So, it's being proposed, somebody wants to build, the Elizabeth Grady people want to propose we build a six, I don't know, six or eight story student housing on that corner.

1773
02:45:30,558 --> 02:45:41,260
[SPEAKER_09]: Even though they say students won't have cars, there'll be Ubers, there'll be Lyft, there'll be Amazon, there'll be FedEx, there'll be food deliveries all out there.

1774
02:45:41,841 --> 02:45:52,803
[SPEAKER_09]: On the other side of the track for Walkley Court, there'll be home health aides, visiting nurses, physical therapists, the ride coming and all this.

1775
02:45:53,243 --> 02:45:58,885
[SPEAKER_09]: So we're going to have all this additional traffic in our street, in addition to the people.

1776
02:45:59,265 --> 02:46:10,870
[SPEAKER_09]: So between Walkling Court and a proposed 600-bed student housing, there would be over 900 people in one corner in a residential neighborhood.

1777
02:46:11,210 --> 02:46:11,930
[SPEAKER_09]: That's too much.

1778
02:46:12,790 --> 02:46:13,391
[SPEAKER_09]: It's too much.

1779
