[SPEAKER_15]: Three houses down the street from me on the other side, that's turned into an Airbnb.

1833
02:50:00,254 --> 02:50:03,415
[SPEAKER_15]: And I know that's not by law, but nobody's enforcing that law.

1834
02:50:04,015 --> 02:50:08,857
[SPEAKER_15]: And the person that owns it is lovely, but still it's not a home for anyone anymore.

1835
02:50:09,497 --> 02:50:15,839
[SPEAKER_15]: On the other side of the street, further down, there's a couple who own their primary residence is here in Florida.

1836
02:50:15,919 --> 02:50:17,600
[SPEAKER_15]: They have a secondary one on the Cape.

1837
02:50:18,080 --> 02:50:24,870
[SPEAKER_15]: And the home that they own on Turnwood Street is empty most of the time, but sometimes serves as an Airbnb.

1838
02:50:25,391 --> 02:50:27,714
[SPEAKER_15]: So my question is not my question.

1839
02:50:27,774 --> 02:50:33,883
[SPEAKER_15]: My point is that we can write all the rules that we want, but in our little area,

1840
02:50:34,539 --> 02:50:40,623
[SPEAKER_15]: they're no longer being owner-occupied dwellings, but rather investors are coming in and using the houses however they want.

1841
02:50:41,044 --> 02:50:49,530
[SPEAKER_15]: So the income doesn't really support Medford, and it doesn't support the community, and the properties aren't really well-maintained, some of them like they used to be.

1842
02:50:51,071 --> 02:50:56,455
[SPEAKER_15]: I also think that there is, like Tufts is a tremendous example.

1843
02:50:56,495 --> 02:51:00,438
[SPEAKER_15]: We had all these people that weren't interested in that

1844
02:51:01,100 --> 02:51:08,388
[SPEAKER_15]: being developed to the heights that it is, but because of a legal loophole, they got to have the building and it's affected and impacted all of us.

1845
02:51:08,908 --> 02:51:19,960
[SPEAKER_15]: So what I'm wondering about is if we have all these incentives toward affordable housing and we have plenty of, it seems like lack of

1846
02:51:21,286 --> 02:51:25,248
[SPEAKER_15]: Regulation for investors that come here and do whatever they want.

1847
02:51:25,789 --> 02:51:27,089
[SPEAKER_15]: What about average people?

1848
02:51:27,570 --> 02:51:35,554
[SPEAKER_15]: Like my story is that I used to live in Cambridge in the in the in the affordable house rent control.

1849
02:51:35,834 --> 02:51:39,016
[SPEAKER_15]: And I was moving every year until I got rent control.

1850
02:51:39,336 --> 02:51:42,678
[SPEAKER_15]: And finally I got that and my life stabilized and I could focus on work.

1851
02:51:43,116 --> 02:51:44,477
[SPEAKER_15]: Then they got rid of rent control.

1852
02:51:44,857 --> 02:51:47,179
[SPEAKER_07]: And then again, sorry to interrupt.

1853
02:51:47,239 --> 02:51:48,020
[SPEAKER_07]: It's been three minutes.

1854
02:51:48,120 --> 02:51:49,942
[SPEAKER_07]: I can only be a short while.

1855
02:51:50,142 --> 02:51:51,843
[SPEAKER_15]: I'll only be a short while more, I promise.

1856
02:51:51,883 --> 02:51:52,964
[SPEAKER_15]: And then I'll put it in writing.

1857
02:51:53,565 --> 02:51:57,448
[SPEAKER_15]: Then I moved finally through supportive family and friends.

1858
02:51:57,488 --> 02:52:01,451
[SPEAKER_15]: I moved into the first home I ever lived in that was owned by someone in my family.

1859
02:52:02,172 --> 02:52:03,273
[SPEAKER_15]: And having that.

1860
02:52:03,780 --> 02:52:05,941
[SPEAKER_15]: allowed me to become middle class.

1861
02:52:06,421 --> 02:52:11,522
[SPEAKER_15]: Having that allowed me to stabilize my career and start pursuing more and more advanced careers.

1862
02:52:12,122 --> 02:52:14,743
[SPEAKER_15]: And that's the delta.

1863
02:52:14,803 --> 02:52:16,483
[SPEAKER_15]: We're not protecting for the middle class.

1864
02:52:16,523 --> 02:52:18,904
[SPEAKER_15]: We're creating and supporting the K economy.

1865
02:52:19,304 --> 02:52:28,747
[SPEAKER_15]: So I just ask us to be really data driven and really mindful of what actions we will take that would truly support an integrated, diverse,

1866
02:52:29,807 --> 02:52:37,970
[SPEAKER_15]: housing situation where people can own their apartments or own their homes and develop their own personal wealth in this community, in this community.

1867
02:52:38,450 --> 02:52:38,730
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you.

1868
02:52:38,770 --> 02:52:39,430
[SPEAKER_07]: I appreciate it.

1869
02:52:39,870 --> 02:52:40,631
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you very much.

1870
02:52:41,531 --> 02:52:44,772
[SPEAKER_07]: Next up here at the at the at the in-person mic.

1871
02:52:45,412 --> 02:52:46,533
[SPEAKER_07]: Name and address of record please.

1872
02:52:46,813 --> 02:52:49,634
[SPEAKER_26]: Hi, Erin DeBenedetto at 21 Dearborn Street.

1873
02:52:54,872 --> 02:52:58,095
[SPEAKER_26]: Hi, I've lived in this area almost 40 years now.

1874
02:52:58,135 --> 02:53:01,899
[SPEAKER_26]: I've raised my children and some of them went to Tufts University.

1875
02:53:02,039 --> 02:53:09,487
[SPEAKER_26]: So I have respect for them in some ways and just feel not so happy with them and many others.

1876
02:53:10,067 --> 02:53:28,179
[SPEAKER_26]: I felt like when they took over the Coho housing, which was Capon Street and all those streets, and changed all those two families into dormitories and put 14 students in each of those two family houses, and they kept it in that area, they kind of pushed out the other people that owned those two families.

1877
02:53:28,219 --> 02:53:33,503
[SPEAKER_26]: I think there's only one left in that area, maybe more, but I know of one.

1878
02:53:34,944 --> 02:53:39,107
[SPEAKER_26]: And I called it the Capon Creep, the university creeping down the hill,

1879
02:53:39,813 --> 02:53:41,314
[SPEAKER_26]: and taking over our neighborhood.

1880
02:53:41,854 --> 02:53:57,920
[SPEAKER_26]: And at that board meeting with zoning, the Tufts lawyers drew a red line about where they would come and how far they would come based on the fact that we could bring so many people to oppose them coming down to that area.

1881
02:53:58,340 --> 02:54:08,144
[SPEAKER_26]: Well, I just found out that Hillside Hardware, which was owned by Walnut Property, which paid taxes to the city, has now just transferred that property over to Tufts.

1882
02:54:08,464 --> 02:54:14,728
[SPEAKER_26]: So that means that we have lost that commercial revenue, the sales revenue, the tax income for that.

1883
02:54:15,048 --> 02:54:17,129
[SPEAKER_26]: And then will they give us a pilot?

1884
02:54:17,490 --> 02:54:24,394
[SPEAKER_26]: When they did the Cummings building, I insisted on a pilot and they paid $250,000 a year, every year for that building.

1885
02:54:24,894 --> 02:54:31,198
[SPEAKER_26]: On the, my point is, this is our chance to zone the corridor and to hold it,

1886
02:54:32,779 --> 02:54:35,723
[SPEAKER_26]: back from losing more revenue for the city.

1887
02:54:36,324 --> 02:54:43,775
[SPEAKER_26]: Also, you know, 700 story, 10 story dorm, what is that doing to our infrastructure?

1888
02:54:43,855 --> 02:54:48,903
[SPEAKER_26]: How is our fire department addressing all, you know, when the elevators don't work, when

1889
02:54:49,263 --> 02:54:51,704
[SPEAKER_26]: there's a problem up there when there's a medical issue.

1890
02:54:51,764 --> 02:54:53,445
[SPEAKER_26]: We have to respond to that as a city.

1891
02:54:53,785 --> 02:54:58,387
[SPEAKER_26]: They only gave one payment of $250,000 one time for that building.

1892
02:54:58,927 --> 02:55:07,971
[SPEAKER_26]: So we are losing money by helping Tufts every single day, and they act like they give so many community upgrades to us.

1893
02:55:08,371 --> 02:55:10,692
[SPEAKER_26]: Now, I served on the pilot committee with

1894
02:55:11,930 --> 02:55:16,715
[SPEAKER_26]: President Beers at one point, and we haven't done that in a long time.

1895
02:55:16,995 --> 02:55:18,657
[SPEAKER_26]: We need to hold them more accountable.

1896
02:55:18,897 --> 02:55:22,540
[SPEAKER_26]: And I would like to see in this zoning that no more

1897
02:55:23,863 --> 02:55:27,867
[SPEAKER_26]: housing for students be allowed on the Boston Ave corridor.

1898
02:55:28,588 --> 02:55:30,230
[SPEAKER_26]: I want that part of your zoning.

1899
02:55:30,891 --> 02:55:36,938
[SPEAKER_26]: I loved all of you this evening in your restricted heights because I don't think we need those heights.

1900
02:55:37,178 --> 02:55:38,319
[SPEAKER_26]: It doesn't warrant it.

1901
02:55:38,600 --> 02:55:39,400
[SPEAKER_26]: We're on a hill.

1902
02:55:39,701 --> 02:55:42,904
[SPEAKER_26]: You build four stories on the hill, you look like six.

1903
02:55:43,996 --> 02:55:45,919
[SPEAKER_26]: You're not, I live down the hill.

1904
02:55:45,979 --> 02:55:49,203
[SPEAKER_26]: My daughter went to Tufts, she could see her bedroom from her dorm room.

1905
02:55:49,684 --> 02:55:52,308
[SPEAKER_26]: That's how close, we walked up first day of school.

1906
02:55:52,588 --> 02:55:55,172
[SPEAKER_26]: She was an RA up there for many years, up in Miller.

1907
02:55:56,450 --> 02:56:01,633
[SPEAKER_26]: And I have respect for the campus in so many ways, but don't feel like they're good neighbors.

1908
02:56:02,013 --> 02:56:19,043
[SPEAKER_26]: I think this is our chance to maximize our hold back, them taking over hillside and taking over revenue from our city and requiring our infrastructure to support their buildings when they don't even want to build them on campus.

