[SPEAKER_11]: I'm sure everybody's really exhausted.

1923
02:57:16,722 --> 02:57:19,864
[SPEAKER_11]: I would like to say first that I do support Doug Carr's comments.

1924
02:57:20,845 --> 02:57:24,167
[SPEAKER_11]: I think one of the big struggles with zoning in general,

1925
02:57:25,380 --> 02:57:36,065
[SPEAKER_11]: is, particularly in a city that probably fell behind in zoning, is this incredible energy to want to push, push, push, push, push, so we have to make up all this lost ground now.

1926
02:57:36,986 --> 02:57:43,609
[SPEAKER_11]: I would urge the city to think twice about that strategy, and I think you do need to moderate the building heights

1927
02:57:44,352 --> 02:57:49,718
[SPEAKER_11]: I think you're going to have a lot of pretty unhappy residents, at least in the hillside, if you don't.

1928
02:57:50,279 --> 02:57:57,186
[SPEAKER_11]: And I also think the city ought to be committing to reviewing zoning changes every three to five years for impact.

1929
02:57:57,787 --> 02:58:02,111
[SPEAKER_11]: Nothing prevents the city from coming back four or five years from now

1930
02:58:02,792 --> 02:58:08,615
[SPEAKER_11]: And changing the zoning again so that you can allow for more gradual change across the neighborhoods.

1931
02:58:09,055 --> 02:58:12,937
[SPEAKER_11]: And I really do think that gradual change is not a curse word.

1932
02:58:13,637 --> 02:58:17,980
[SPEAKER_11]: And I think that when you have really polarized views,

1933
02:58:18,760 --> 02:58:22,262
[SPEAKER_11]: that moderation can really be what is needed.

1934
02:58:22,682 --> 02:58:25,644
[SPEAKER_11]: I do think that the city clearly needs more tax revenue.

1935
02:58:26,024 --> 02:58:34,989
[SPEAKER_11]: I'm not jonesing to approve another tax override in November to fund a high school as somebody who's sort of on a fixed income.

1936
02:58:35,689 --> 02:58:40,992
[SPEAKER_11]: But so I completely appreciate the need for additional tax revenues in the city.

1937
02:58:41,092 --> 02:58:46,515
[SPEAKER_11]: I think that has to be one of the main drivers for zoning changes in this town.

1938
02:58:48,236 --> 02:58:55,199
[SPEAKER_11]: I will say I have an issue with the word density and I kind of wish people would define it because it's actually not a defined word.

1939
02:58:55,600 --> 02:58:58,081
[SPEAKER_11]: Everyone talks about increasing density, but to what?

1940
02:58:59,350 --> 02:59:12,856
[SPEAKER_11]: And since that's a completely unanswered question in my view, at least I haven't heard a reasonable definition of it, I just assume that it is undefined because it's a really difficult thing to define.

1941
02:59:12,956 --> 02:59:21,180
[SPEAKER_11]: And that's another reason to look at moderation in zoning changes across a number of years rather than in one big bang.

1942
02:59:21,920 --> 02:59:26,382
[SPEAKER_11]: The last thing that I'll say is very specific to the dorm proposal for the corner of North

1943
02:59:27,908 --> 02:59:31,649
[SPEAKER_11]: For other reasons than many people, first of all, I don't think it's needed.

1944
02:59:32,149 --> 02:59:40,932
[SPEAKER_11]: And if somebody from Northeastern is living in Medford, I do pity them because, you know, the Green Line could help, but it's going to be a long commute because I went to Northeastern.

1945
02:59:42,813 --> 02:59:43,753
[SPEAKER_11]: I don't think we need it.

1946
02:59:43,833 --> 02:59:50,655
[SPEAKER_11]: And I don't think my concern is that I don't know that there's any difference in the context that we're talking about it than an apartment building.

1947
02:59:51,535 --> 02:59:55,520
[SPEAKER_11]: It's not under the auspices of an educational institution.

1948
02:59:56,041 --> 03:00:01,167
[SPEAKER_11]: There are not resident assistants living in the building to help regulate that building.

1949
03:00:01,587 --> 03:00:09,136
[SPEAKER_11]: There's no independent police department who citizens can call to complain about issues related to that private dorm.

1950
03:00:10,077 --> 03:00:22,799
[SPEAKER_11]: And so I would caution us that this is actually not something that the city of Medford needs at this time and would completely support tabling that completely in this zoning pass.

1951
03:00:23,379 --> 03:00:24,460
[SPEAKER_11]: That's it for me, folks.

1952
03:00:24,500 --> 03:00:26,660
[SPEAKER_11]: Thank you so much for all the work.

1953
03:00:26,780 --> 03:00:29,960
[SPEAKER_11]: I know you're all exhausted and I can understand it.

1954
03:00:31,101 --> 03:00:31,561
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you, Judy.

1955
03:00:31,581 --> 03:00:32,141
[SPEAKER_07]: Appreciate it.

1956
03:00:32,501 --> 03:00:34,881
[SPEAKER_07]: Is there anyone else in the room who would like to speak?

1957
03:00:34,901 --> 03:00:36,522
[SPEAKER_07]: Go ahead.

